(2, 'Home', 'Anas', 1, 1, '<div class="bb-item" id="item1"><div class="pagenum">1/13</div><div class="content page1" style="background-image:url(http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/1.jpg)"><div class="scroller" style="text-align:center"><div class="frontpage">        <h2>Threads</h2>        <div style="float:right"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/2.jpg" style="width:100px"/></div>        <p>Volume I, Issue I March 2016</p>        <p>Official Newsletter</p>        <p>Department of Computer Science and Engineering</p>      </div></div></div></div>'),
(3, 'Message from HOD', 'Abdul Nazeer', 1, 2, '<div class="bb-item" id="item2">  <div class="pagenum">2/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>Message from the HOD<br/></h2>        <p class="author">- <em><a href="http://www.nitc.ac.in/index.php/?url=users/view/359/38">Dr. Abdul Nazeer K A</a></em></p>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-6">              <p>It’s really heartening to note that the Computer Science and Engineering Association is bringing out a Newsletter highlighting the recent trends in the rapidly changing CS scenario.</p>              <p>Being the trend-setters for many innovative activities in our campus, CSE Association has got the remarkable reputation of being one of the most vibrant student groups of NITC.  I am really delighted to note that our kids are continuing to uphold this tradition with greater enthusiasm and vigor.</p>            </div>            <div class="col-md-6">                <p>I sincerely hope that this Newsletter will serve as a unique platform for reflecting the hidden talents of our students and to showcase the amazing array of activities being hosted by CSEA. With the active involvement of our illustrious alumni also, this will go a long way in strengthening the bond of our CSED fraternity.</p>                <p>On behalf of the entire ‘CSED Family’, I wholeheartedly congratulate the ‘Team CSEA’ and wish All the Best for this noble endeavor.</p>                <p>May God Bless you all.</p>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(4, 'Editorial', 'Aishu', 1, 3, '<div class="bb-item" id="item3">  <div class="pagenum">3/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>Editorial</h2>        <p class="author">- <em>Aishwarya Maruvada, Student Editor</em></p>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-6">              <p>“Sometimes it is the people who no one imagines anything of who do the things that no one can imagine.” </p>              <p>Every mathematician or a computer scientist would have dreamt of reaching great heights as high as those scaled by Mr. Alan Turing. This man, a brilliant mathematician, logistician and cryptanalyst, needs no further introduction. His contribution to the field of theoretical computer science shaped this field as we see it today.</p>              <p>The first issue of the official newsletter of the Department of Computer Science and Engineering, NIT Calicut pays homage to him. The machine, named after its inventor, is a simple yet a highly powerful mathematical model used to simulate the logic of any algorithm. </p>              <p>This newsletter, aptly named Threads, refers not only to its relevance in the field of Operating Systems but also to the fact that it is the little things are often the most important.</p>            </div>            <div class="col-md-6">              <p>The purpose of this newsletter is to share knowledge, tit bits and updates from the ever-changing CS scenario. This newsletter will feature articles from our current students, alumni, updates from the Free and Open Source community apart from an informal section for our coders and hackers to take lighthearted breaks after their long hours at work. This issue came into light only due to the creativity and toil of several students who put in their best effort. </p>              <p>My heartfelt gratitude to Dr. Vinod Pathari sir, Staff Editor without whom this would have not been possible. My sincere thanks to the Head of the Department, Dr. K. A Abdul Nazeer and to the CSEA faculty incharges, Dr. S. D. Madhukumar and Ms. A. Lijiya for their support. </p>              <p>Happy Reading!<br/><em>Aishwarya, Student Editor, Threads</em></p>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(5, 'Solving Problems', 'Aashish', 1, 4, '<div class="bb-item" id="item4">  <div class="pagenum"><!--?php echo ++$page; ?-->/<!--?php echo $total; ?--></div>  <div class="content page2">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">          <h3>Solving Problems By Making Them Harder!?</h3>          <p class="author">- <em>Aashish Satyajith, B.Tech IIIrd year</em></p>          <div class="container-fluid">            <div class="row">              <div class="col-md-6">                <p>Time and again we’ve been told by our betters that if we can’t solve a problem, try to solve a simpler version of the same problem.                  And the advice has worked out pretty well too. But would it be actually possible to solve a problem by making it harder than it originally is?                  Let’s find out!!                </p>                <p>                  Imagine (imagine!) that the Department of Computer Science has been allotted some new land as a part of expansion of the campus.                  Some of the land was decided to be used to honour an iconic figure in the field of computer science: Alan Turing.                  To do this, a big square courtyard would be constructed, divided into unit squares, at the centre of which a statue of Alan Turing would be placed in a single unit square.                   Recognizing the importance of the binary system, we insist that the dimensions of the square be a power of two.                </p>                <p>                  We hire a genius architect, Jed Mosley, to get the job done. As we all know, Jed (like most geniuses) is a little bit eccentric, and <i>he</i> insists that the tiles used for the courtyard be of a particular L-shape as such:                </p>                <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/14.jpg"/></div>                <p>The next figure then represents a valid tiling:</p>                <div class="img"><img src="./images/articles/validtile.jpg"/></div>                <p>But now, we have problem. How exactly are we supposed to know that there’s going to be a valid tiling for any n that we choose? How do we know, that after the tiling, there would be a square left in the centre to place Turing’s statue? Is there a way out?</p>                <p>Challenge accepted. We need to prove that there’s a valid tiling leaving a square in the centre empty for any n that we choose. Well the only two proof techniques that we’re largely familiar with are proof by induction and proof by contradiction, and the latter doesn’t seem to be the guy for the job. Onward with induction then:</p>                <p><strong>Attempt #1:</strong></p>                <p>Let P(n) be the proposition that there exists a tiling of a 2<sup>n</sup> x 2<sup>n</sup> courtyard with a square remaining empty in the centre.</p>                <p><strong>Base case: </strong>P(0) is obviously true, since at n = 0, all we have is a 1 x 1 square and we can put Turing’s statue there.</p>                <p><strong>Inductive step:</strong>  Assume that  P(n) is true. We must prove that there is a way to tile a 2<sup>n+1</sup> x 2<sup>n+1</sup> courtyard with a square empty in the centre, i.e. that P(n + 1) is true.</p>                <p>We divide the 2<sup>n+1</sup> x 2<sup>n+1</sup> courtyard into four, and we get four squares of dimension 2<sup>n</sup> each. Each 2<sup>n</sup> x 2<sup>n</sup> square has a square at its centre empty, by the induction hypothesis.</p>                <p>Uh oh...trouble!! We can’t bring together the four empty squares in the centre of the four “quadrants” to form a tiling with one empty square!! In other words, we can’t prove this hypothesis!! Ah...nostalgia from that last discrete math exam ;-)</p>                <p>Well we''re not giving up yet, let’s chuck the old hypothesis and start with a new one:</p>              </div>              <div class="col-md-6">                <p><strong>Attack #2:</strong></p>                <p><strong>Proof:</strong> Let P(n) be the proposition that there exists a tiling of a 2<sup>n</sup> x 2<sup>n</sup> courtyard with a square remaining empty <i>ANYWHERE</i> we want.</p>                <p>At this point, you’re probably saying: “Wait – what!? Life is already difficult enough as it is trying to prove the hypothesis for a SINGLE square and now you want to try to prove the hypothesis for ALL the squares? Are you out of your mind!?”</p>                <p>Relax. This is a standard technique in induction: if you can’t prove an inductive hypothesis, try to prove a - wait for it - grander one. How does that help us? Allow me to demonstrate:</p>                <p><strong>Base case:</strong> P(0) is true as earlier – because there’s only one square, we can just put the statue there.</p>                <p><strong>Inductive step:</strong> Assume that P(n) is true.</p>                <p>Now to prove that P(n + 1) is true:</p>                <p>As earlier we split up the 2<sup>n + 1</sup> x 2<sup>n + 1</sup> square into four and obtain squares of dimension 2<sup>n</sup> x 2<sup>n</sup> each. Place Turing''s statue anywhere in the one of these squares (marked S in the picture below). Because we’re guaranteed to find a single square empty in each of the four quadrants wherever we want them (that''s the induction hypothesis), let’s put the empty squares in the remaining three squares of each 2<sup>n</sup> x 2<sup>n</sup> square as such:</p>                <div class="img"><img src="./images/articles/statue.png"/></div>                <p>Now the rest is pretty obvious: place an L-shaped tile covering the squares marked X!! And so P(n) implies P(n + 1), and by principle of mathematical induction, the statement is true for all n!! And since we can place Turing''s statue anywhere now, it follows that we can place it at the center. All of us (including Jed) can go home happy!!</p>                <p>So in a way we managed to get to the solution by making our problem harder than it originally was. How did that work? It worked because induction works by assuming that whatever we’re trying to prove is true. The stronger the hypothesis, the more...liberal...our assumption is. In our case, assuming that you can have an empty square <i>anywhere</i> in the 2<sup>n</sup> square turned out to be far more powerful than assuming that you can have a square (specifically) at the centre. We simply exploited this as a tool to get to our solution.</p>                <p>And that’s how you solve problems by making them harder :-)</p>                <p>P. S. Did you notice something else? The proof actually gives an algorithm to find a tiling!! Can you work out the details?</p>                <p></p>                <p><i>Adapted from Mathematics for Computer Science, Leighton et al (2012). A print version of this book has not been published yet.</i></p>              </div>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>  </div></div>'),
(6, 'Internships and beyond', 'Ayush', 1, 5, '<div class="bb-item" id="item5">  <div class="pagenum"><!--?php echo ++$page; ?-->/<!--?php echo $total; ?--></div>    <div class="content page3">      <div class="scroller">        <div class="light">          <div class="container-fluid">            <div class="row">              <div class="col-xs-8">                <h3 style="text-align:right">Internships and Beyond</h3>                <p style="text-align:right">-<em> <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/jaiswalayush1">Ayush Jaiswal</a>, B.Tech 2014 batch alumnus</em></p>              </div>              <div class="col-xs-4">                <img style="width:200px;max-width:100%" src="./images/articles/ayush.jpg"/>              </div>          </div>        </div>          <div class="container-fluid">            <div class="row">              <div class="col-md-6">                <p>As college students, we all know how important internships are in shaping our careers. I remember my classmates running around trying to get letters of recommendation as early as at the beginning of the third semester. Although an internship after the third year of BTech is an absolute must for both getting a good job after graduation and for applying for higher studies, an internship after the second year helps boost one’s profile for graduate school applications more than job applications.</p>                <p>There are a lot of internship opportunities available for Computer Science students with the increase in the number of tech companies and research programs at various universities within and outside India. I am going to talk exclusively about research-based internships here, because I know better about them through first-hand experience. CSEA does a really good job at spreading awareness about these through the annual internship talk, but something I found slightly disappointing was that very few people actually apply to these programs to avail of these remarkable opportunities.</p>                <p>In my conversations with fellow classmates and juniors, I found that most of them felt that they were not qualified enough for the internship programs, especially those outside India, and so they did not apply. Through this article, I would like to encourage all the current students to apply to these opportunities. You will never know until you actually apply. It is all about demand and supply. Perhaps you have something they are looking for, but if you do not apply in the first place, you will never get it. It is like a self-fulfilling prophecy.</p>                <p>I know this because when I was applying for research internships at universities outside India in my third year, I was very confident that I would not get into any of them. That was mainly because I had heard so much about the IIT bias and also the fact that I had no prior research experience. I felt like it was a vicious cycle: you need research experience to get a research internship and you need the latter for the former too, but as it turned out, this was not the case. I got accepted into a lot of programs, leaving me completely surprised (pleasantly).</p>              </div>              <div class="col-md-6">                <p>I am not saying that you do not need a good profile to get accepted, but I knew people who had good profiles and yet did not apply. I would like to encourage you to not be one such person. If you are still in your first or second year, you have a lot of time to work on your profile. The easiest way is to complete online courses in your area of interest within Computer Science. There are multiple options available now: Coursera, Udacity and edX among others. Completing such courses and doing some project work shows that you are motivated and focused, which is something people look for when they review internship applications.</p>                  <p>But is it really worth the effort to apply to these programs? Filling up long forms and getting the required supporting documents from college is in fact very time-consuming. I think it is totally worth it. Through my internship, I got to learn a lot of new things. It also helped me develop skills in working on my own and as a team. I learned how to look at a problem from different perspectives to come up with novel solutions. These internships also come with a huge benefit of research-related letters of recommendation, which is a big plus for graduate school applications, especially if you are applying for a PhD. This, again, is from my first-hand experience.</p>                  <p>I know that a lot of you reading this article have not even thought about higher studies, but I see it as a way of keeping that door open. It will only add plus points to your profile, and who knows, maybe the internship will motivate you to pursue higher education. Personally, I had never thought of doing a PhD, but during my internship, I enjoyed research so much that I started applying for graduate school programs as soon as I came back.</p>                  <p>All in all, I hope I was successful in somewhat demystifying research-based internships and encouraging you to at least consider applying. I found the website www.internshala.com very helpful in finding information about these programs and I urge you to visit it. Good luck!</p>              </div>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div>'),
(7, 'Csea Updates', 'idk', 1, 6, '<div class="bb-item" id="item6">  <div class="pagenum white">4/13</div>  <div class="content page4" style="background-image:url(http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/3.jpg)">    <div class="scroller">      <h2>CSEA Updates</h2>      <hr/><br/>      <div class="container-fluid">        <div class="row">          <div class="col-md-6">            <ul class="whitetux">                <li>FOSSMeet 2016 was successfully conducted, witnessing a foot fall of over 170 people. <a href="http://fossmeet.in/">(Website)</a></li><br/>                <li>C-SCAN (Computer Science Conference of All NITs) was successfully conducted. <a href="http://cscan.org.in/">(Website)</a></li><br/>                <li>Linux Workshop was conducted to teach basic linux commands. Presentation available <a href="http://athena.nitc.ac.in/piyush_b130057cs/Linux_Workshop/Slide/index.html#/">here</a></li><br/>                <li>A Git workshop was conducted to teach the basics of Git, a version control system.</li><br/>            </ul>          </div>          <div class="col-md-6">            <ul class="whitetux">                <li>A 5-week Android workshop is ongoing with more than 60 registered participants. Presentation available <a href="http://athena.nitc.ac.in/piyush_b130057cs/Android_Workshop/index.html#/">here</a></li><br/>                <li>A talk on &#34;Extracting Performance from next gen Intel Architecture&#34; from <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/austin-cherian-ab07703">Austin Cherian</a>, Business Development Manager was conducted successfully</li><br/>                <li>A workshop on &#34;Rust Programming Language&#34; was conducted by <a href="http://nibrahim.net.in/">Noufal Ibrahim</a></li><br/>            </ul>          </div>        </div>        <br/><h4 style="font-size: 1.25em;">For more information, visit our <a href="http://cse.nitc.ac.in/">website</a>. Also follow us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/CSEA.NITC/">Facebook</a>!</h4>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(8, 'Opportunities', 'idk', 1, 7, '<div class="bb-item" id="item7">  <div class="pagenum">6/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>Opportunities Galore</h2>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-6">              <ul class="blacktux">                <li>IIIT Allahabad has opened call for its <a href="https://www.iiita.ac.in/downloads/announcements/uploads/Summer%20Research%20Internships%20Program%202016386.pdf">Summer Internship Programme 2015</a> and will accept applications till 15<sup>th</sup> April.</li>                <li>IIT Guwahati is hosting a <a href="https://www.iitg.ernet.in/cseweb/summerinternship/home">Summer Internship Program</a>. This one has its deadline late in March.</li>                <li>IIT Bhubaneswar''s <a href="http://webapps.iitbbs.ac.in/internship-application/">Internship Programme for Summer</a> also has its deadline late in March.</li>                <li>IIT Ropar''s portal for <a href="http://www.iitrpr.ac.in/summer-internship">internship applications</a> will be open till 28<sup>th</sup> March.</li>                <li>Also, don''t miss out on some amazing learning opportunities at a few startups.</li>              </ul>            </div>            <div class="col-md-6">              <h3><strong>Featured</strong></h3>              <h3>Google Summer of Code 2016</h3>              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/4.jpg"/></div>              <h4>Students'' application start from March 14, 2016. Keep track at <a href="https://www.google-melange.com/">Google Summer of Code</a></h4>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(9, 'Upcoming Coding Contests', 'idk', 1, 8, '<div class="bb-item" id="item8">  <div class="pagenum">8/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>Upcoming Coding Contests</h2>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-6">                <ul class="whitetux">                    <li><a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/march-clash-16/">March Clash 2016</a></li><br/>                    <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/7.jpg"/></div><br/>                    <li><a href="https://www.hackerrank.com/hourrank-7">Hour Rank 7</a></li><br/>                    <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/9.jpg"/></div><br/>                </ul>            </div>            <div class="col-md-6">                <ul class="whitetux">                    <li><a href="https://www.codechef.com/MARCH16">March Long Challenge</a></li><br/>                    <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/8.jpg"/></div><br/>                    <li><a href="http://www.codeforces.com/contests/637">V K Cup on Codeforces</a></li><br/>                    <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/10.jpg"/></div><br/>                </ul>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(10, 'Gadget Gizmo', 'Anshul,Piyush', 1, 9, '<div class="bb-item" id="item9">  <div class="pagenum">9/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>Gadget Gizmo</h2>        <p class="author">- <em>Anshul Chokhani &amp; Piyush Bhopalka</em></p>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-6">              <p>The <strong>Asus Chromebit</strong> is a HDMI dongle, which can be connected to a display (TV/ Monitor) to bring Chrome OS functionality to them. Sometime back, Google had unveiled Chromecast, a HDMI dongle which was basically extending a second screen from your phone, tablet or your Chromebook onto the big screen. However, this time in partnership with Asus, Google has released a full OS on a pendrive-like device.                  Imagine the time when an OS used to come in CDs and after spending hours on installation, we would finally end up with a system that could do tasks that even feature phones can do today with ease.                  Recent advancements have made it possible to simply plug and play an OS and Chromebit is a perfect example for it. It has been available in India since January for a MRP of Rs 7,999<sup>[1]</sup>. </p>            <p>Chromebit is a powerful device and an innovative product. Using a light-weight OS like Chrome OS, Asus and Google have taken a right decision                to turn a normal TV/monitor without the need for an external CPU into a full-fledged computer.</p>            </div>            <div class="col-md-6">                <p><strong>Asus Chromebit specifications and features: </strong></p>                <p>On the hardware front, it is powered by a Rockchip 3288 ARM-based processor paired with 2GB of RAM and 16GB of onboard storage. The Chromebit also includes connectivity options such as Wi-Fi 802.11ac, Bluetooth 4.0 and a USB 2.0 port.                  The USB 2.0 port on the dongle lets you connect peripherals such as a USB mouse or keyboard, a pen drive or an external hard disk.</p>                <br/>                <div class="img"><img src="./images/articles/dongle.JPG"/></div>              </div>          </div>          <br/>          <sup>[1]</sup> : On <i>http://www.amazon.in</i> as of 24<sup>th</sup> February 2016<br/>          Asus is a trademark of Asus Inc. and Chromebit and Chrome OS are trademarks of Google Inc.        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(11, 'FossMeet 2016', 'Idk', 1, 10, '<div class="bb-item" id="item10">  <div class="pagenum">10/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>FOSSMeet 2016</h2>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-6">              <div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">                <h3>FOSSMeet conducted successfully!<br/></h3>                <a href="http://www.fossmeet.in"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/13.jpg" class="img-responsive"/></a>              </div>            </div>            <div class="col-md-6">              <ul>                  <h3>Highlights during FOSSMeet 2016</h3>                  <hr/>  <br/>                  <h4>The Worst Programmer I ever met - Steven Deobald</h4>                  <p>Relationships are hard. Software is hard. FOSS communities often represent the most difficult intersection of these two axes.Attendees will come out with practical lessons and tools for working in teams, bettering themselves, and avoiding some of software’s most expensive mistakes.                  </p><br/>                  <h4>Golang Workshop - Baiju M</h4>                  <p>                      This workshop taught the fundamentals of Go programming language. The workshop included setting up environment for Go development, basic syntax, concepts and solving few problems.                  </p><br/>                  <h4>Building your own Hackable Keyboard - Abhas Abhinav</h4>                  <p>                      We all use keyboards. And not all of us care enough about them to ensure that, like our operating systems, they are hackable too. What could be better than to                      build your own keyboard using open hardware designs and components and then program it using free / open source software?                  </p><br/>                  <h4>Introduction to LaTeX and Friends - Sasi Kumar</h4>                  <p>                      Sasi Kumar''s talk on LaTeX and Friends was all about writing documents in LaTeX a breeze, which is a must-have skill in the academia.                      the academia.                  </p><br/>                  <h4>And Many More...</h4>              </ul>            </div>          </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(12, 'The Little Grey Cells Attack', 'Idk', 1, 11, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n    <title>\r\n    </title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item9">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            <!--?php echo ++$page; ?-->/<!--?php echo $total; ?-->\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>The Little Grey Cells Attack</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p class="title">The famous Pirates puzzle</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>5 pirates of different ages have a treasure of 100 gold coins. On their ship, they decide to split the coins using this scheme: The oldest pirate proposes how to share the coins, the OTHER pirates (not including the oldest) will vote for or against it. If 50% or more of the pirates vote for it, then the coins will be shared that way. Otherwise, the pirate proposing the scheme will be thrown overboard, and the process is repeated with the pirates that remain. Assuming that all 5 pirates are intelligent, rational, greedy, and do not wish to die, (and are rather good at math for pirates) what will happen?</p>\r\n\r\n                                <hr>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="title">Puzzle 2</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>A man is caught on the King''s property. He is brought before the King to be punished.&nbsp; The King says, &#34;You must give me a statement. If it is true, you will be killed by lions. If it is false, you will be killed by trampling of wild buffalo.&#34; But in the end, the King has to let the man go. What was the man''s statement?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><i>These puzzles can be found at <a href="http://puzzles4you.blogspot.in/">puzzles4you.blogspot.in</a>.</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p class="title">Puzzle 3</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>A warden of a jail decides to have some fun one day... he decides he will give three prisoners a chance to go free... but only if they can prove themselves worthy of being released! The warden brings out five hats, three of them red and two of them blue. The three prisoners are then blindfolded and one of the hats, at random, is placed on each of their heads. He lines up each prisoner in a row, facing a brick wall. The blindfolds are then removed. Prisoner C can see both Prisoners A and B and the color hats that each of them is wearing. Prisoner B can only see Prisoner A and his hat. Prisoner A, being in the front, cannot see any hats. And no prisoner can, of course, see the color of his own hat.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>The problem he puts to the prisoners is simple: &#34;If you can determine the color of the hat on your own head, I will release you from this prison. If you answer incorrectly, I will add another 20 years to your sentence! However, if you do not know and choose not to answer at all, nothing will come of it.&#34; He first asks Prisoner C, &#34;What is the color of the hat on your head?&#34; Prisoner C thinks for a short while and then replies, &#34;I''m sorry, I do not know.&#34; He then asks Prisoner B, &#34;What is the color of the hat on your head?&#34; Prisoner B thinks for a short while and then also replies, &#34;I''m sorry, I do not know.&#34; He finally asks Prisoner A, &#34;What is the color of the hat on your head?&#34; Prisoner A thinks for a short while and then replies, &#34;I know! The color of my hat is....&#34; What color hat is Prisoner A wearing and how did he know?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><i>This puzzle and more can be found <a href="https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~wwu/riddles/hard.shtml">here</a>.</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(13, 'FUNtastic', 'Idk', 1, 12, '<div class="bb-item" id="item12">  <div class="pagenum">12/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>FUNtastic</h2>        <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/11.jpg"/></div>        <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/12.jpg"/></div>        <p><i>These files are from <a href="http://xkcd.com/">xkcd.com</a>. Content from xkcd is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 2.5 License.Details and usage notes can be found <a href="http://xkcd.com/license.html">here</a>.</i></p>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(14, 'The Team', 'Csea', 1, 13, '<div class="bb-item" id="item13">  <div class="pagenum">13/13</div>  <div class="content">    <div class="scroller">      <div class="light">        <h2>The Team</h2>        <div class="container-fluid">          <div class="row">            <div class="col-md-4"></div>            <div class="col-md-4">              <h4 class="team">Editors</h4>              <ul class="special">                <li><a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aashishsatya">Aashish Satyajith</a></li>                <li><a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aishwarya-maruvada-30136672">Aishwarya Maruvada</a></li>                <li><a href="https://github.com/anshulchokhani">Anshul Chokhani</a></li>                <li><a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aparna-jairaj-884751b1">Aparna Jairaj</a></li>                <li><a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/pbhopalka">Piyush Bhopalka</a></li>                <li><a href="http://people.cse.nitc.ac.in/pathari/">Vinod Pathari</a></li>              </ul>              <h4 class="team">Designers</h4>              <ul class="special">                <li><a href="https://github.com/anasanzari">Anas Ansari</a></li>                <li><a href="https://www.facebook.com/satya.darls?fref=ts">K Satya Kumar</a></li>              </ul>            </div>            <div class="col-md-4"></div>            </div>            <div class="row">              <div class="col-md-12">                <div class="socialbuttons">                  <a class="social" href="https://www.facebook.com/CSEA.NITC">                    <img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/5.jpg"/>                  </a>                  <a class="social" href="http://assoc.cse.nitc.ac.in">                    <img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/6.jpg"/>                  </a>                </div>                <p class="center">Suggestions for improvement are welcome.</p>                <p class="center">We are now accepting articles for our next issues. Please drop us a mail at <a href="mailto:csed.newsletter@gmail.com" target="_top">csed.newsletter@gmail.com</a></p>              </div>            </div>        </div>      </div>    </div>  </div></div>'),
(15, 'Home', 'Anas', 2, 1, '<div class="bb-item" id="item1"><div class="pagenum">1/12</div><div class="content page1" style="background-image:url(http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/14.jpg)"><div class="scroller" style="text-align:center"><div class="frontpage">        <h2>Threads</h2>        <div style="float:right"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/2.jpg" style="width:100px"/></div>        <p>Volume I, Issue II July 2016</p>        <p>Official Newsletter</p>        <p>Department of Computer Science and Engineering</p>      </div></div></div></div>'),
(16, 'Lifi - Wifi but using light', 'Piyush Bhopalka', 2, 7, '<div class="bb-item" id="item7">  \r\n<div class="pagenum">7/12</div>\r\n<div class="content page2">    \r\n<style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n.newul li{\r\n list-style: disc outside none;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</style>\r\n    <div class="scroller">      \r\n    <div class="light">          \r\n        <h2>Lifi - WiFi but using light</h2>          \r\n        <p class="author">- <em>Piyush Bhopalka, B. Tech. CSE 2017 Batch</em></p>          \r\n        \r\n        <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <p>\r\nLifi, a term coined by Prof. Harald Hass at TEDGlobal 2011, is the next big technological advancement that the world has seen. It refers to ‘light’ based communication technology that delivers a high-speed, bidirectional networked, mobile communications in a similar manner as Wifi.\r\n                </p>\r\n                <p>                 \r\nThe idea is very simple. Wifi uses radio frequencies to transmit data which lies in the electromagnetic spectrum. Visible light also belongs to this same electromagnetic spectrum and has higher frequencies than radio frequency. If communication can be made possible by using this higher frequency wave spectrum, more data can be transferred in a cheaper rate. Moreover since light is one of the most prominent radiation that we observe in our daily life, lesser effort will have to be made for its deployment. Developing on this idea, pureLifi is bringing the technology to the real world. The tests are still going on and the technology is not ready to be used prime-time, but the future is bright. \r\n                </p>\r\n\r\n                <p class="title">How Lifi works?</p>\r\n\r\n                <p>\r\nLifi uses visible light as a means of transmitting data. In an LED light bulb, when a constant current is applied, a stream of photons are emitted and these are what we observe as visible light. If current is varied, the light intensity changes. Since LED light bulbs are semiconductor devices, the output from it can be modulated at extremely high speeds, undetected by human eyes but easily detectable by a photo-detector device, which can then convert it back to electrical current.Thus communication becomes possible with the help of visible light.        \r\n                </p><br>\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                \r\n                <p class="title">A few features of Lifi</p>\r\n                <ul class="newul">\r\n                        <li>\r\nBandwidth - Visible light spectrum is unused and free to use.\r\n                        </li>\r\n                        <li>\r\nLow cost - Requires fewer components than required to set up Wifi\r\n                        </li>\r\n                        <li>\r\nHigh Speed - Very high speed data rates can be obtained due to low interference, high device bandwidths and high intensity optical output\r\n                        </li>\r\n                        <li>\r\nSafe - Life on earth has evolved through exposure to visible light and there are no known safety or health hazards against visible light\r\n                        </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n                </div>            \r\n            </div>          \r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n      </div>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>'),
(17, 'CSEA Updates', 'Piyush Bhopalka', 2, 6, '    <div class="bb-item" id="item6">\r\n        <div class="pagenum white">\r\n            6/12\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class="content page" style="background-image:url(http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/18.jpg); background-size:cover">\r\n        <div class="scroller">\r\n\r\n<style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n.newul li{\r\n list-style: disc outside none;\r\n}\r\n\r\n</style>\r\n                \r\n               \r\n                <div class="container-fluid">\r\n\r\n                    <div class="row">\r\n<h2>CSEA Updates</h2>\r\n <hr>\r\n                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                            <ul class="newul">\r\n                                <li>The 5-week Android workshop came to a\r\n                                conclusion. Evaluation of the projects done by\r\n                                the participants were done which was followed\r\n                                by Certificate Distribution.</li>\r\n                                <li>A 2-day JavaScript workshop was held for\r\n                                the first year students. The objective was to\r\n                                familiarize them with the general patterns in\r\n                                programming and how a knowledge of one language\r\n                                can be used to learn another language at ease.\r\n                                In this case, using knowledge learnt in C to\r\n                                learn Javascript.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                            <ul class="newul">\r\n                                <li>A placement talk was conducted with the\r\n                                help from the 4th year students, in the\r\n                                presence of Prof. T K Suresh Babu, HOD, T&amp;P\r\n                                and Dr. Abdul Nazeer, HOD, CS Department. The\r\n                                second and third year students were briefed\r\n                                about the various internship opportunities\r\n                                available and the strategies and resources to\r\n                                prepare for the placement season.</li>\r\n                                <li>A small alumni meet was conducted where\r\n                                alumni from different batches came and attended\r\n                                the event. An interactive session between the\r\n                                faculties, students and the alumni was held.\r\n                                Preparation work for the next alumni meet to be\r\n                                conducted next year started.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n'),
(19, 'CSED Farewell', 'CSEA Executives', 2, 9, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item9">\r\n    <div class="pagenum">9/11</div>\r\n \r\n <div class="vid" style="position:relative;width:100%;text-align:center;padding-top:100px">\r\n    \r\n\r\n<iframe width="800" height="475" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cPBks7AEAI8" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n \r\n  </div>\r\n\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `name`, `author`, `edition`, `number`, `content`) VALUES
(21, 'What after Computer Science Degree?', 'Muhammad Yazar, B. Tech (2009-', 2, 3, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item3">\r\n    <div class="pagenum">3/12</div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>What after Computer Science Degree?</h2>\r\n          <p class="author">- <em>Muhammad Yazar, B. Tech. CSE 2014 Batch (Alumnus)</em></p>\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n                                    <div class="col-xs-8 col-xs-offset-2"><img class="img-responsive" src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/20.jpg">\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                <br>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n              \r\n                <p>It is a very common question for most Computer Science students as to what are the options that one can pursue after graduating with a degree in Computer Science and Engineering. This article will give you a very high level idea of all career paths possible for you to take up, after a Bachelors degree in CS. The article will also provide a very brief description of the competencies and skills required when you opt for each of these career paths.\r\n                </p><br>\r\n                <p class="title"> Software Development, SW Test / QA Engg, Support Engg. etc: </p>\r\n                <p>\r\nThis is the most common and the immediate career path which a Computer Science Graduate can opt for. The nature of work varies from one company to another and also depends on the job profile. For Software Engineering profiles, you need to be a good programmer. Apart from just programming from scratch, you may also be spending time on adding new features over the existing code base, gathering requirements from clients, designing the software architecture etc. Some companies, especially the big ones will have a lot of quality enforcement on the software pieces they develop, as each element will have many issues involving customers in case of presence of any bugs. As your experience increases in the Software engineering profiles, you may move shift towards the design / architecture of software systems. In some companies, you may get specialized programming tasks like Network programming, Linux Kernel module development etc. Before applying for a company, it is strongly recommended that you to catch up with someone at the company working in the same profile and try to understand how the nature of work will be.\r\n\r\n                </p><br>\r\n                <p class="title">What about joining a Startup?</p>\r\n                <p>\r\nYes, of course it is a good idea, but there are few things which you need to be very careful about. The problem with big companies is that the work may get narrowed down over some part of a big software and the contribution of an individual to the work may be very less. While working in some other companies, it can even end up in having very less time for coding, and more time on other activities like collecting the requirements, preparing documents etc. In Start-Ups, generally, you may get really good quality work, but sometimes you may end up working over time. You need to check the following factors before going for a startup:<br><br>\r\n●     What are they working on? Can you see a really good scope for this in future as well?<br><br>\r\n●     Who started it? Is it being run by someone who is really into innovation?\r\n                </p><br>\r\n                <p class="title">Specialized Computer Science Jobs / Research & Development:</p>\r\n                <p>\r\nSpecialized Computer Science careers means job profiles like: Machine Learning Scientist, Compiler Engineering, Kernel Engineer etc, and also various Research and Development jobs in core Computer Science domains or in interdisciplinary branches like Computational Neuroscience, Quantum Computing, BioInformatics etc. These kind of jobs are well suited for those who are really passionate about some particular domain in Computer Science and those who want to make some really impactful innovations. Most of these profiles require you to have at least a masters in the relevant subjects to get into them. Sometimes after gaining relevant experience in the Software Industry, one may be able to switch to specialized jobs. For example you can move as a Kernel Developer after having working in some domains of Linux Systems / Kernel module development. If  the difference between the general Software Engineering jobs and these specialized profiles is prodded upon, an example can be cited: In big companies, Machine Learning Scientists / R&D teams develops the algorithms / models for machine learning and the Software Engineers uses the libraries developed by them to implement Machine Learning in various systems. If you are planning to take up this path, then it is strongly recommended not to stop your studies with just an undergraduate degree. At least before the end of your third year try to figure out the areas you would like to focus further. Also make sure to explore various domains(especially inter disciplinary) and see if they suit your interest. Try to do your final year project in the area which you try to focus in the future.\r\n                </p>\r\n                <p class="title">Higher Studies in Computer Science:</p>\r\n<p>\r\nUnless you are planning to continue in Software Engineering job profiles, it is strongly recommended to go for education beyond graduation. There are post graduate courses by various universities which can help you enhance your career in Software Engineering. Specialization in a particular domain improves your chance of working in more core technologies.\r\n </p>\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">                \r\n<p class="title">Higher Studies in Computer Science:</p>\r\n<p>\r\nUnless you are planning to continue in Software Engineering job profiles, it is strongly recommended to go for education beyond graduation. There are post graduate courses by various universities which can help you enhance your career in Software Engineering. Specialization in a particular domain improves your chance of working in more core technologies.\r\n </p>\r\n \r\n<p class="title">Higher Studies Abroad:</p>\r\n<p>\r\nMost of the foreign universities are taking a considerable number of students from India and you will definitely have a really high chance of getting in easily. If you are planning for higher studies, these are the things that are recommended to plan during your studies:<br>\r\n●     Do a really good final year project on the domain you would like to specialize in future. Also, try to do some other projects outside curriculum in the related domains.<br>\r\n●     Maintain a good CGPA.<br>\r\n●     Try to publish a paper. This really enhances your chance of getting into a top college.<br>\r\n●     Try to do a summer research internship in the area you would like to study further.<br><br>\r\nAfter working for few years in some company you can still plan for your further studies and if the work in the company is in a relevant technology which you would like to specialize, it really improves your chance of getting into a good university. There is also an option to opt for PhD directly after graduation. For this you need to be more focused on the domain during your studies and should have proper projects with research elements, as it is a little harder compared to getting into masters programme.\r\n </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="title">Careers in Academics + Research:</p>\r\n<p>\r\nIf you have an interest in sharing knowledge with others and shaping the future generations, then you should go for this holy profession. Nowadays, especially in foreign universities, a career as an Academician is not merely teaching. The faculties will be scientists and they will be continuously working on their researches. Various companies fund for the projects / researches. This will be a good profession if you want to keep learning always in your life and continually research on areas you like.\r\n </p>\r\n \r\n<p class="title">Management Careers:</p>\r\n<p>\r\nIf you interest is not towards Computer Science / Programming and if it is towards managing or coordinating projects / processes, then there is always an option to opt for management jobs. There are various options in the management side like: Finance Management, Human Resource Management, Production Management, Business Analysis etc. Preferably you need to pursue an MBA (or some other post graduate degree in business) to get into management profiles. You can also get into after these profiles after having enough work experience. You can also move to Software Development Management profiles and for that you should have some experience as a Software Engineer.\r\n</p> \r\n\r\n<p class="title">Making a Start Up:</p>\r\n<p>\r\nIf you have some really innovative idea in your mind, at some point in your life, then you should think about making a startup. Apple, Google, Amazon, Microsoft and all the big companies now were some small startups at some point of time, which were started by people like you. Before starting a firm think properly what innovation it is going to make in the society, how it is going to generate revenue in future etc. Now there is a lot of support from government and other private organizations for startups. If you are not confident enough to implement it immediately, then you can join some startup / companies for few years and by then you may learn more strategies on running a firm yourself.\r\n</p>\r\n \r\n<p class="title">General advice while in college:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n●     Practice programing properly and be really good in at least one programming language. Programming is always required whichever career path you choose in Computer Science.<br>\r\n●     Never learn anything just for grades. Approach subjects with a passion. Learn properly, even outside the curriculum, at least one domain. Try to code and implement yourself the features in the area which you are interested in. For example, if you are interested in Cryptography, try to implement all the Crypto Algorithms yourself and evaluate it.<br>\r\n●     Take your major project seriously. Try to make some innovation out of it and publish a paper. Also try to do other projects yourself.<br>\r\n●     Make sure to enjoy your college life. This is the best part of your life and make it always memorable. Enjoy the Calicut city, try out all the varieties of food, for which Calicut city is famous. Be a part of Tathva, Ragam and other activities in college. <br>\r\n              </p><br>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->'),
(22, 'FUNtastic', 'Aparna', 2, 11, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n    <title>\r\n    </title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item11">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            11/12\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>FUNtastic</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-12">\r\n                                <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/16.jpg">\r\n                                </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/17.jpg">\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><i>These files are from <a href="http://xkcd.com/">xkcd.com</a>. Content from xkcd is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 2.5 License.Details and usage notes can be found <a href="http://xkcd.com/license.html">here</a>.</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <!-- row-->\r\n                    </div>\r\n                    <!--containerfluid-->\r\n                </div>\r\n                <!--light div-->\r\n            </div>\r\n            <!--scroller-->\r\n        </div>\r\n        <!--content -->\r\n    </div>\r\n    <!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(23, 'Puzzles', 'Aparna', 2, 10, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n    <title>\r\n    </title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item10">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            10/12\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>Puzzles</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <h3>Puzzle 1:</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>A and B are twins; A is the older twin. Assume they were born immediately after each other, an infinitesimally small - but nonzero - amount of time apart. During one year in the course of their lives, A celebrates her birthday two days after B does. How is this possible?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><i>This puzzle can be found at <a href="https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~wwu/cgi-bin/yabb/YaBB.cgi?board=riddles_hard;action=display;num=1027807787">ocf.berkeley.edu</a>.</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <h3>Puzzle 2:</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>You are travelling in the jungles of Africa, when you are caught by a tribe of barbarians. They allow you to choose between death or solving their great challenge: You are blindfolded and taken to a room, where you are asked to kneel. You feel hundreds of circular discs lying in front of you. You are told that one side of each disc is painted red, and the other, green. There are exactly 129 discs that currently are red side up. You have to divide the discs into two groups, such that each group has the same number of discs showing the red colour. Obviously, no peeking allowed.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <h3>Puzzle 3:</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>There is a Kingdom, a King, and a Queen. An carnival is scheduled after 35 days in the Kingdom. The King orders 1000 bottles of wine for the carnival . The Queen wants to kill the King. Queen sends an assassin to mix poison in ONE of the 1000 bottles. The effect of the poison is such that the person who took it, will die after 30 days. Somehow the King happened to know about the conspiracy, and want to know about the poisonous bottle. The King has 10 prisoners on whom he can use the wine to test, whether its poisonous. How the King is going to find out the poisonous bottle within 35 days.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><i>Puzzles 2 and 3 can be found <a href="https://www.quora.com/What-are-some-interesting-puzzles-asked-in-computer-science-programming-technical-interviews#!n=12">here</a>.</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                    <!--containerfluid-->\r\n                </div>\r\n                <!--light div-->\r\n            </div>\r\n            <!--scroller-->\r\n        </div>\r\n        <!--content -->\r\n    </div>\r\n    <!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(24, 'Editorial', 'Team Threads', 2, 2, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item2">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">2/12</div>\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>Editorial</h2>\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <h3>"Perfecting oneself is as much unlearning as it is learning."<br></h3>\r\n                        <h5 style="text-align: right">-Edsger W. Dijkstra</h5>\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p><br>\r\n                                We are really glad to have brought out the second issue of Threads, our department newsletter. As much as we would love to believe in the philosophy of ''Well begun is half done'', the first issue which was released in the month of March has received appreciation from student and teaching fraternities alike. But that did put immense pressure on us to outdo ourselves to bring out a better version and hence the delay in the same.</p>\r\n                                <p>The highlight of this issue, which we would term as the special summer issue, is an interview we got to do with the most loved faculty member of our department, Dr Vineeth Paleri sir. We would like to thank him for sparing us his valuable time and definitely, the experience of interviewing him was terrific.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p><br>\r\n                                Apart from this, we have an article by our 2014 batch alumnus, Muhammed Yazar on the possible paths one could pursue after graduation. We also have the usual updates from CSED, the FOSS world and some comics to keep you engaged.</p>\r\n                                <p>We hope you enjoy this issue as much as we enjoyed the journey of effort we put in to complete it.</p>\r\n                                <p>- Team Threads</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n                </div><!--light div-->\r\n            </div><!--scroller-->\r\n        </div><!--content -->\r\n    </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(25, 'Heart to Heart with Paleri sir', 'Aishwarya Maruvada, K Prasad K', 2, 4, '\r\n\r\n    <style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n    blockquote {\r\n    font-family: Georgia, serif;\r\n    font-size: 18px;\r\n    font-style: italic;\r\n    width: 500px;\r\n    margin: 0.25em 0;\r\n    padding: 0.25em 40px;\r\n    line-height: 1.45;\r\n    position: relative;\r\n    color: #383838;\r\n    border-left: none;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    blockquote:before {\r\n    display: block;\r\n    content: "\\201C";\r\n    font-size: 80px;\r\n    position: absolute;\r\n    left: -10px;\r\n    top: -20px;\r\n    color: #7a7a7a;\r\n    }\r\n    </style>\r\n\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item4">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            4/12\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content page2">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h3>Heart to Heart with Paleri sir</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p class="author">- <em>Aishwarya Maruvada & K Prasad Krishnan, B. Tech. CSE 2016 Batch</em></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <div class="row">\r\n                                    <div class="col-xs-8 col-xs-offset-2"><img class="img-responsive" src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/19.jpg">\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <br>\r\n                                \r\n                                <p><i>Dr. Vineeth Paleri has been a part of the teaching faculty at NIT Calicut in various roles from 1986. He received his Bachelors degree in Electrical Engineering from NIT Calicut in 1981. He completed his Masters in Technology from IIT Kanpur in 1986. Further, he went on to pursue a PhD degree from Indian Institute of Science, Bangalore and was awarded the same in 1999. His primary research interests center around Programming Languages and Compilers. He has held several prestigious positions, serving as the Head of the Department of Computer Science and Engineering (July 2008 - July 2010) and has also been a Member of the Board of Governors, NIT Calicut (March 2013 - March 2015). He currently serves as the Secretary of the Technology Business Incubator here at NIT Calicut (a position he''s held from September 2009).</i></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>A quote by William Arthur Ward goes,</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <blockquote>\r\n                                    The mediocre teacher tells. The good teacher explains. The superior teacher demonstrates. The great teacher inspires.\r\n                                </blockquote>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Well, there is one such teacher who has been an inspiration to the many batches of students that our department has produced. The teacher we have all looked up to. The teacher whom we have feared at some point or the other. The teacher who taught us the importance of being brief and precise. And probably the only teacher in our department who even has a fan club on Facebook to his honor. We have seen the way he handles his classes with utmost sincerity and dedication, the uniqueness that sets him apart so much that most students attend his classes right from day one to his very last class in a semester, regardless of attendance that most students crave for. So when we got an opportunity to interview him for Threads, our department newsletter, we were indeed elated. On the day of the interview when we stood outside CSE 201C, frankly we were a bit scared too, apart from being thoroughly excited. And forty minutes later, when the interview got over we realized that we would cherish the very experience every time we would look back at our college life.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>So here is the complete interview for you all to enjoy:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What is about teaching that you find most enjoyable and also most challenging?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> It was incidental that I came to the teaching profession. After completing my Bachelors degree, I had told my friends that the one thing I won''t be doing is coming back to teach. But it was purely a coincidence. After around four years of passing out from here, I came back as a teacher. From that point onwards, I''ll say that, I haven''t regretted it. Rather, I have enjoyed it. And I feel that it is really a challenge for any teacher to convey whatever he wants to, identifying what exactly has to be conveyed, not whatever is there in a textbook. But as a teacher, we have to identify what to convey and that does take a long time and then conveying the things so that the students understand it, by making it simple: this is not an easy job. And it is only after 10-15 years of teaching the same subject that I am able to convey it a simple manner. Initially, I just studied whatever was in the textbook, using standard textbooks of course and delivered it. But now, I use the reference textbooks, now I decide what needs to be conveyed, what needn’t be conveyed and I choose my own examples, simplified if possible which comes through experience.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What is that you like the most about the field of CS and personally having done your Bachelors in EE, how was the transition for you and what propelled you to do so?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> When I passed out from here with a basic degree in Electrical Engineering, there was an elective subject in my seventh semester which was basically CS or Computer Engineering which dealt with the digital fundamentals and somehow I was interested in that subject. I wanted to take a Masters at an IIT, that is in the field of digital systems at some IIT. Then I went to IIT Kanpur, before which I joined here for a Masters programme which I quit after 2 months. Then I went to IITK for a Masters programme in Digital Systems, I wrote the entrance test and passed it. I failed in the interview and I didn’t get an admission there. I still remember how they asked some fundamental questions in EE namely superposition theorem etc. and I made some mistakes. Then I thought, if I make some mistakes in the fundamentals, I don''t deserve any good universities. So I gracefully accepted that. Luckily there was a programme called Computer Trainee at the computer centre at IITK and I applied and I got through. After one year, there was another colleague of mine in that programme, a B. Tech (Chemical Engineering) from IITK. One day he asked me, shall we write GATE in CS (first ever GATE in the field of CSE). I asked him if he was joking and I also added that coming from a EE background it is not an easy job. Then he said, we will write in CS. He was of the opinion that there are only very few institutes that offer B. Tech. in CS. He advised that we needn''t compete with IITians, instead only NITians. Finally, I found that he was talking logic. We took the syllabus, prepared and wrote GATE. Out of the 108 people who wrote, I came 40th and he came 41st. We both didn’t get admission anywhere based on the score we got. Next year I got admission at IIT Kanpur and he at IIT Bombay based on the interview conducted by these IITs.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> Who is the one person who has had the most powerful impact on you, your research and your career?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> As far as academics is concerned, it is Prof. Dijkstra who has influenced me profoundly. In the sense that I don’t find an article of that calibre written by anybody else even after 40 years. I don''t find the kind of articles he has written and influence on me regarding all those things as far the discipline of CS is concerned. Wherever I go, I ask students what their discipline is, is it Computing Science or Computer Science, it all came by clarity from Dijkstra.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What is it that motivated you to come back to your Alma Mater as faculty?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> It was not my desire, again a coincidence. After my M. Tech in IIT Kanpur, I thought of only public sector jobs, I didn’t want to go for private sector companies. So I was trying for a couple of companies like CMC but couldn’t get through. Finally, I landed in TCIL (Telecommunications Consultants India Limited) in Delhi. I was supposed to join and they asked for two testimonials. By mistake, I assumed that they had asked only one. But then when I went to submit the documents, they said I needed to submit two testimonials. So I said I''d join with those two testimonials after a few days. My cousin was with me then, we came back to his house and there was a letter waiting for me from my classmate from NITC, Suresh Manimala. He came for an Alumni meet here and meet the Principal at that time, Prof. Unnikrishna Pillai. Coming back for your previous question as to who influenced me, Academics it is Dijkstra and in Administration, I haven’t seen a person like Prof. Pillai. I wasn’t sure at all by now and I was uncomfortable thinking of what I would tell TCIL. I asked for a month’s extension to join. Then, I came here, met Prof. Pillai. He said with my qualification, I could make it easily but then I told him that I needed time to decide. Finally, I took the decision to come here and met Prof. Pillai again. He immediately contacted Prof. M. N. Neelakantan, the HOD of Computer Engineering, the registrar and conducted the interview. Then I was offered the job on a temporary basis and then I came aboard.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What is your most favourite course to teach and what is the best research project you enjoyed working on? <b></b></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> As far as teaching is concerned, you know that my area is Compilers and with Dijkstra''s influence, programming was at the background all the time. But Compilers was my core area. Because of Dijkstra''s influences, you can see that there is a FOP course which has undergone a lot of changes over the time. FOP is one such course that you won''t find in many places in India and it is indeed a very important course. As far as research is concerned, I went to St. Petersburg, Russia under the USSR Govt. Doctoral Scholarship.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>I was introduced to formal models of concurrent computing that time, then I came back without completing the programme and landed in IISc, Bangalore for my Ph.D. I still remember, by about a year or so, the problem was clear and I had to go deeper and deeper for the solution, which was basically a simple algorithm for partial redundancy elimination which I consider the best algorithm till date. People haven''t agreed fully but they have accepted it. Since then, we have been working on code optimization but I still remember this particular algorithm.</p>\r\n                                \r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> How different would you term your teaching experiences here and abroad?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> So to sum up, this was what I felt in my office at Purdue and that was, there is a lot of time to teach here, unlike in NIT Calicut, back then when there was a lot of other work. But in Purdue, they gave all the time to deliver to my satisfaction and better pay as well.</p>\r\n\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n								\r\n								<p><b>Team:</b> And what about the students? The quality of education?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> As far as students are concerned, people may not know this, but if I need to compare the standard of students, looking only at UG students, the calibre of the students was below the quality of students at NIT Calicut. But things change completely when it comes to Masters program, as Purdue gets the best students from all over the world.</p>\r\n								\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> Who is the one colleague or friend you admire the most and why?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> That is a question that I am not able to give a precise answer. Ummm… (thinking) he was my classmate here and we had a lot of professional interaction. He is my friend, Dr. Suresh Manimala. He is the only person with whom I can discuss anything, professional or otherwise, all my secrets included.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> How do you keep your students’ attention up and going, in your classes?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> I would say, I try my best in terms of my preparation. Luckily, my students gave me feedback that my voice is audible even at the back of the classroom. Secondly, I have been trying hard to make sure of what I am supposed to convey to the class and then, I try to make it as simple as possible. I feel that the effort to make it simple, make sure that the lectures are understood, that is very necessary.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> Coming to the next question based on the previous question, your classes have always been organized and well executed? How do you manage this?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> Well, there is a clear plan. I have the complete notes in hand. I don’t give them to the students but I make sure that I have it. The notes were made with a lot of effort and over the years, I changed a few examples and even now, before any class, I jot down the basic points that I need to deliver.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> You have always expected brief and precise and answers from us in all your question papers. So how do you implement the CS principles of simplicity, preciseness and abstraction in your life?</p>\r\n                                \r\n                                <blockquote>\r\n                                    Even at home, I make sure that I complete my duties without worrying about other distractions.\r\n                                </blockquote>\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> One thing I noticed is that, which is from Dijkstra, if you want to do something in an excellent fashion, you have to focus on that which is fundamental. The chief takeaway from Dijkstra is separation of concerns. Even at home, I make sure that I complete my duties without worrying about other distractions. Basically because I know that it may affect my duties. Anything you do, try to do to the best of your ability, otherwise you try to avoid it, if possible.</p>\r\n                                \r\n                                <blockquote>\r\n                                    Anything you do, try to do to the best of your ability, otherwise you try to avoid it, if possible.\r\n                                </blockquote>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What accomplishments of yours are you the most proud of?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> Once in a while, I get a feedback from my students that my teaching is good, I think that is what keeps me going, trying to teach better. It does make a lot of difference.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> How has interacting with your students changed you as a person and as a teacher?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> As a teacher, I would say that there have been students all the time who were demanding, so that made me improve myself. So essentially, if you don’t have students who are demanding, I think you''d get demotivated. Well, there is a conviction that you should essentially try to simplify and maybe I should add here, one of the quotes that drives me in both personal and professional life is one from Charles Mingus that goes, ''Making the simple complicated is commonplace; making the complicated simple, awesomely simple, that is creativity''. A good teacher will never tell that some particular topic is difficult. If a teacher says so, it essentially means that he is not fully clear about something about that topic. If he knows it well, then where does the difficulty lie?</p>\r\n                                \r\n                                <blockquote>\r\n                                    A good teacher will never tell that some particular topic is difficult. If a teacher says so, it essentially means that he is not fully clear about something about that topic.\r\n                                </blockquote>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> Going back to your student life, what is it that you enjoyed the most in college?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> Back then, it was not like how it is now. It took five years for the programme. And there were a lot of sport activities at REC Calicut. We were University champions for the 10th consecutive year when I passed out. I was a part of sports activities. I consider myself more of an introvert till pre-degree and it is here that I changed a lot and I think sports played a serious role in that.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> Which sport did you play in college? (On popular demand :P)</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> Initially, I was a long distance runner. I would wake up early every morning and set out to practice. Then later, my classmate introduced me to wrestling. Then, we had a vigorous training for two months by a Kerala coach and I stood first in college and second in University level for two consecutive years.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>(And we, Team Threads, were left in a state of awe on hearing this).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What do you miss the most about college?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> Maybe the fact that I didn''t get to spend my time in college like the current era of students. Looking back, I feel that it could have been more colorful.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What is the fondest memory you have of our college?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> As I already introduced, Suresh Manimala, my classmate and a dear friend was inclined towards arts. As a side note, he was the music director of a movie that released in the year 2010, Paattinte Palazhy, which didn''t succeed very well, unfortunately. However, I still remember taking the college bus and going to Farook college for the Kalolsavam there. Apart from that, visits to Providence college as a group and returning in the buses, sitting on the top. *Sir chuckles at the fond memories*</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What are your favorite hobbies?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> Hardly any, explicitly. But I do try to read books. Earlier, I would read all the Malayalam classics and slowly turned towards English novels. But I was never fond of poetry. I feel I am more of a logic person and poetry requires a different bend of mind.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> What is the secret behind being so active and self-motivated?</p>\r\n                                \r\n                                <blockquote>\r\n                                    For example, in research, my aim is that I need to produce at least one paper from NIT Calicut that is world class. That''s my goal.\r\n                                </blockquote>\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> I want to improve in everything I do. I want to give in my best, rather I don''t want to do things half-baked. Whatever I take up, I try to do it to the best of my ability. For example, in research, my aim is that I need to produce at least one paper from NIT Calicut that is world class. That''s my goal.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Team:</b> On a parting note, what is the one advice that you''d like to give your students?</p>\r\n                                \r\n                                <blockquote>\r\n                                    The most crucial advice is always take the righteous path. If at any point in time, you feel that you are not on the right path, just take a deviation because only at your deathbed will you realize that you had been committing a mistake all along.\r\n                                </blockquote>\r\n\r\n                                <p><b>Paleri sir:</b> As I already mentioned in the Department farewell of the 2016 pass out batch, as Dijkstra rightly said, be careful while giving advices because sometimes students end up following advices. *Laughs* On a professional note, students should know the difference between computer science and computing science and should be very clear of the discipline so that they can end up in a meaningful job. This is because they shouldn''t face dejection as far as career is concerned. For example, a real computer programmer should be a developer and not a tester which is merely a technician role. And on a personal note, I''d say that many a time, we tend to make mistakes. But what we need to do is to identify our true potential, whatever it maybe and build on it. The most crucial advice is always take the righteous path. If at any point in time, you feel that you are not on the right path, just take a deviation because only at your deathbed will you realize that you had been committing a mistake all along.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>And that brings us to the end of this article and once again we would like to add that we are indeed very grateful to him for having spared us his time to learn more about his life beyond what students see in the classroom.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `name`, `author`, `edition`, `number`, `content`) VALUES
(26, 'The Busy Beaver Problem', 'Deepak Sirone and Arpan Kapoor', 2, 5, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n\r\n    <script async src="https://cdn.mathjax.org/mathjax/latest/MathJax.js?config=TeX-MML-AM_CHTML" type="text/javascript">\r\n    </script>\r\n\r\n    <title>\r\n    </title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item5">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            5/12\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content page2">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h3>The Busy Beaver Problem</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p class="author">- <em>Deepak Sirone & Arpan Kapoor, B. Tech. CSE 2016 Batch</em></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p>A function is a mapping from an input to an output such that each input produces exactly one output. However, the notion of a function does not define the algorithm to get from the input to the output. This means that using this definition of functions, you have the freedom to define your own functions, provided you can specify the domain and range precisely. So a function which outputs the number of sand grains in the Sahara desert at a particular instant of time is perfectly legal! This however does not ensure that there exists an algorithm to do it.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Such functions that are definable by an algorithm are called computable functions. There also exists functions which can be proved to not have an algorithm and they are called non-computable functions. One such function known as the Busy Beaver function was defined by Timos Rado in his 1961 paper "On Non-Computable Functions".</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>The busy beaver function is concerned with a model of executing algorithms known as Turing machines. A Turing machine is a machine which has an infinite bidirectional input/output tape, a tape head and rules governing the movement of the tape head on the tape. The tape is divided into cells and the symbols written on the tape are from an alphabet \\(\\Sigma\\).Similar to a finite state machine, a Turing machine has a set of states, \\(Q\\) and a transition function \\(\\delta\\). The tape head reads one symbol on the tape at a time and based on the transition function, overwrites the symbol with another symbol and shifts (steps either right or left on the tape<sup>1</sup>. The Turing machine also has a halt state whereby the machine stops running. The running time of a Turing machine on an input is measured as the number of shifts it performs before it enters its halting configuration. A binary Turing machine is one with \\(\\Sigma = \\{0 , 1\\}\\).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Not all Turing machines stop running on its given input. The problem of determining whether a Turing machine \\(M\\) halts on input \\(x\\) is known as the halting problem. The halting problem has been shown to be undecidable, meaning that there is no Turing machine (or algorithm for that matter) to solve it. We could try simulating a given machine, to see if it stops after a while. But the problem is that we don''t know for how long the simulation should continue. Suppose we simulate a Turing machine \\(M\\) on input \\(x\\) using another Turing machine<sup>2</sup> for \\(t\\) steps and conclude that it does not halt, we can always find another Turing machine \\(M''\\) which halts on input \\(x\\) in \\(t + 1\\) steps. Hence simulation does not work.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Turns out that the Turing machine model can simulate circuits (both sequential and combinational) and hence we can safely conclude that it is capable of simulating all algorithms that can be run on a real computer.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>We call a binary Turing Machine a \\(k\\)-state Busy Beaver if on an empty tape as input it halts and runs for at least as many steps as any other \\(k\\)-state binary Turing machine.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>In order to find a \\(k\\)-state Busy Beaver, we would have to evaluate all \\(k\\)-state binary Turing machines. How many such Turing machines exist?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p style="font-size:90%;"><sup>1</sup>&nbsp;The Turing machine which we define here does not have a center shift, meaning that the tape head must move left or right after each move.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p style="font-size:90%;"><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;called the Universal Turing Machine or UTM</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p>Since we have fixed the cardinality of Q and the alphabet (\\(\\Sigma = \\{0, 1\\}\\)), the number of possible Turing machines is equal to the number of possible transition functions. The transition function''s domain is the cross product of the set of states with the alphabet and codomain is the cross product of the set of states, the alphabet and the set \\(\\{L, R\\}\\).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>\\[\\delta: Q \\times \\Sigma \\rightarrow Q \\times \\Sigma \\times \\{L, R\\}\\] \\[|Q| = k\\] \\[|\\Sigma| = 2\\] \\[|\\{L, R\\}| = 2\\]</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>From the above, we see that there are \\({(2 \\times 2 \\times k)}^{2k}\\), i.e. \\({(4k)}^{2k}\\) number of \\(k\\)-state binary Turing machines.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>The Busy Beaver function''s input is a positive integer \\(n\\) and it outputs the number of steps taken by a \\(n\\)-state Busy Beaver Turing machine to halt. Assuming this function to be computable gives us the following algorithm to solve the halting problem, which we know is not possible. Hence our assumption must be wrong.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p style="font-family:courier;"><b>function</b> HALTS? (M, x)<br>\r\n                                &nbsp;&nbsp; k = |M.Q| // number of states of the Turing machine M<br>\r\n                                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;bbk = BB(k) // Number of steps taken by a k-state Busy Beaver<br>\r\n                                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>if</b> UTM(M, x, bbk) <b>then return</b> HALTS // UTM simulates M on input x for bbk steps<br>\r\n                                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>else return</b> DOES NOT HALT<br>\r\n                                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>end if</b><br>\r\n                                <b>end function</b><br></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Another interesting fact that can be observed using the same argument is that the Busy Beaver function grows faster than all computable functions, i.e. \\(f(n) = O(BB(n))\\) for any computable function \\(f\\). This is because if some computable function \\(f\\) grew faster than the Busy Beaver function, the function call to BB in the above algorithm can be replaced with a call to this function \\(f\\), enabling us to solve the halting problem. Again our assumption would be wrong. The table below shows what we know currently about the busy beaver series.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>\r\n                                </p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <table align="center" border="1" style="width:100%">\r\n                                    <tr>\r\n                                        <td align="center">\r\n                                        </td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">2 state</td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">3 state</td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">4 state</td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">5 state</td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">6 state</td>\r\n                                    </tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <tr>\r\n                                        <td align="center">BB</td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center"><b>\\(6\\)</b>\r\n                                        </td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center"><b>\\(21\\)</b>\r\n                                        </td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center"><b>\\(107\\)</b>\r\n                                        </td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">\\(\\geq 47,176,870\\)</td>\r\n\r\n                                        <td align="center">\\(&gt; 7.4 \\times 10^{36534}\\)</td>\r\n                                    </tr>\r\n                                </table>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>\r\n                                </p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>So far only we know the exact values of the busy beaver series upto 4 state turing machines. The Busy Beaver series suggests a new method for solving theoretical problems in mathematics. For example, suppose we have a Turing machine \\(M\\) which verifies Goldbach''s conjecture(which states that every even number \\(n\\), \\(n &gt; = 4\\) is the sum of two primes) and it has \\(k\\) states. If we were able to find \\(BB(k)\\) exactly then we could run \\(M\\) for \\(BB(k)\\) steps and conclude that the conjecture holds if it does not stop within that many steps, else we conclude that the conjecture does not hold.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(27, 'The Team', 'CSEA', 2, 12, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n    <title>\r\n    </title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item12">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            12/12\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>The Team</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4 col-md-offset-3">\r\n                                <h4 class="team">Editors</h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ul class="special">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aashishsatya">Aashish Satyajith</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aishwarya-maruvada-30136672">Aishwarya Maruvada</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aparna-jairaj-884751b1">Aparna Jairaj</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/prasad-krishnan-954a61108">K Prasad Krishnan</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/pbhopalka">Piyush Bhopalka</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="http://people.cse.nitc.ac.in/pathari/">Vinod Pathari</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4">\r\n                                <h4 class="team">Designers</h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ul class="special">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://github.com/anasanzari">Anas Ansari</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://www.facebook.com/satya.darls?fref=ts">K Satya Kumar</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4">\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-12">\r\n                                <div class="socialbuttons">\r\n                                    <a class="social" href="https://www.facebook.com/CSEA.NITC"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/5.jpg"></a> <a class="social" href="http://assoc.cse.nitc.ac.in"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/6.jpg"></a>\r\n                                </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="center">Suggestions for improvement are welcome.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="center">We are now accepting articles for our next issues. Please drop us a mail at <a href="mailto:csed.newsletter@gmail.com" target="_top">csed.newsletter@gmail.com</a></p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(28, 'Upcoming coding contests', 'Piyush Bhopalka', 2, 8, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item8">\r\n    <div class="pagenum"></div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>Upcoming coding contests</h2>\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h3>Practice Challenges</h3><br>\r\n                <ul>\r\n                    <li>101 Hack 39 on <a href="https://www.hackerrank.com/contests/101hack39/">Hackerrank</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>July Clash ''16 on <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/july-clash-16/">Hackerearth</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>July Lunchtime on <a href="https://www.codechef.com/LTIME38">Codechef</a></li><br>\r\n                </ul>\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h4>From Companies</h4><br>\r\n                    <ul>\r\n                        <li>Mastermaze by Hewlett Packard on July 15, 6:00 pm <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/hpemastermaze/">(Contest Link)</a></li><br><br>\r\n                        <li>Mokriya iOS Hiring Challenge on July 23, 12:00 pm <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/mokriya-ios-hiring-challenge/">(Contest Link)</a></li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(29, 'Solve These Puzzles', 'Rachna', 3, 10, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item10">\r\n    <div class="pagenum">9/10</div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2><strong>Solve These Puzzles</strong></h2>\r\n<p class="author">- <em>Team Threads</em></p>\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h3> Puzzle  1 </h3>\r\n                <p>You’ve got someone working for you for seven days and a gold bar to pay him. The gold bar is segmented into seven connected pieces. You must give them a piece of gold at the end of every day. What and where are the fewest number of cuts to the bar of gold that will allow you to pay him 1/7th each day?</p>\r\n\r\n              \r\n               <h3>Puzzle  2</h3>\r\n               <p>One day, Mr. Puzzle and Mr. Fry were playing cards, but suddenly power went off and they were getting bored. So Mr. Puzzle randomly inverted position of 15 cards out of 52 cards(and shuffled it) and asked Mr. Fry to divide the card in two pile with equal number of inverted cards(number of cards in each pile need not be equal). It was very dark in the room and Mr. Fry could not see the cards, after thinking a bit Mr. Fry divided the cards in two piles and quite surprisingly on counting number of inverted cards in both the piles were equal. What do you think Mr. Fry must have done?</p>\r\n                 \r\n\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h3>Puzzle  3</h3>\r\n                <p>Three cannibals and three anthropologists have to cross a river. The boat they have is only big enough for two people. The cannibals will do as requested, even if they are on the other side of the river, with one exception. If at any point in time there are more cannibals on one side of the river than anthropologists, the cannibals will eat them. What plan can the anthropologists use for crossing the river so they don’t get eaten? Note: One anthropologist can not control two cannibals on land, nor can one anthropologist on land control two cannibals on the boat if they are all on the same side of the river. This means an anthropologist will not survive being rowed across the river by a cannibal if there is one cannibal on the other side.</p>\r\n\r\n                <p>Solutions to Puzzles 1, 2 and 3 can be found <a href="http://puzzlefry.com/puzzles/">over here</a></p>\r\n\r\n                <h3>Puzzle  4</h3><p>Geeks are too good at solving logical problems. But, this time a Multiple Choice Question was put in front of them having only three options .</p>\r\n                <p>Q. There is only one correct answer to this question. Which answer is this?</p>\r\n                <p> A. Answer A</p>\r\n                        <p>B. Answer A or B</p>\r\n                        <p>C. Answer B or C</p>\r\n\r\n                        <p>Geeks are stuck at this question. Help them out.</p>\r\n   \r\n                <p>Solution can be found <a href="http://quiz.geeksforgeeks.org/">over here</a></p>                 \r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->'),
(30, 'FUNtastic', 'Pavithra', 3, 11, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item11">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            11/12\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>FUNtastic</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-12">\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/23.jpg">\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p><i>(This file is from <a href="http://xkcd.com/">xkcd.com</a>. Content from xkcd is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 2.5 License.Details and usage notes can be found <a href="http://xkcd.com/license.html">here)</a>.</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <!-- row-->\r\n                    </div>\r\n                    <!--containerfluid-->\r\n                </div>\r\n                <!--light div-->\r\n            </div>\r\n            <!--scroller-->\r\n        </div>\r\n        <!--content -->\r\n    </div>\r\n    <!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(31, 'Things I wish I knew in College', 'Kartik Singhal, B. Tech CSE Ba', 3, 4, '<style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n.karthik .light a {\r\n  color: #0084FF;\r\n}\r\n.karthik .light a:hover {\r\n  color: #3B5998;\r\n}\r\n.karthik ol li {\r\n  font-size: 1.2em;\r\n  padding: 10px 5px;\r\n  margin: 0px 10px;\r\n  text-align: justify;\r\n}\r\n.karthik ol li p {\r\n  margin: 0px;\r\n  padding: 0px;\r\n}\r\n.karthik .col-md-6 ul li {\r\n  font-size: 1em;\r\n}\r\n.karthik .col-md-6 ol li p {\r\n  font-size: 1.0em;\r\n  line-height: 1.0;\r\n  font-weight: 300;\r\n  padding: 5px 5px;\r\n  text-align: justify;\r\n}\r\n.karthik blockquote {\r\n  margin-left: 20px;\r\n  margin-right: 20px;\r\n  font-style: italic;\r\n}\r\n.karthik q {\r\n  font-style: italic;\r\n}\r\n.karthik .col-md-6 ol li blockquote p {\r\n  font-size: 1.0em;\r\n  line-height: 1.6;\r\n  font-weight: 300;\r\n  text-align: justify;\r\n}\r\n.karthik dt {\r\n  font-size: 2em;\r\n  font-weight: 350;\r\n  margin-top: 1.2em;\r\n  margin-bottom: 0.2em;\r\n}\r\n.karthik dl {\r\n  margin-bottom: 1.2em;\r\n}\r\n.karthik ol {\r\n  padding-left: 5em;\r\n}\r\n.karthik hr {\r\n  margin-top: 1.2em;\r\n  margin-bottom: 1.2em;\r\n}\r\n					\r\n</style>\r\n\r\n				<div class="bb-item karthik" id="item4">\r\n					<div class="pagenum">3/10\r\n					</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="content">\r\n						<div class="scroller">\r\n							<div class="light">\r\n								<h2>Things I wish I knew in College</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p class="author">- <em>Kartik Singhal, BTech CSE 2009-2013 Batch</em></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<div class="container-fluid">\r\n									<div class="row">\r\n										<div class="container-fluid">\r\n											<div class="row">\r\n												<div class="col-md-6">\r\n													<h3><a id="Meta_2"></a>Meta</h3>\r\n													<p>About a month ago, I asked the following question to the CSE student body:</p>\r\n													<blockquote>\r\n														<p>If you could ask only one question to an NITC CSE alumnus with diverse experience in industry, higher studies, and research, what would you?</p>\r\n													</blockquote>\r\n													<p>The most raised concerns were:</p>\r\n													<ol>\r\n														<li>How to decide between higher studies and industry as your next career move?</li>\r\n														<li>What are the limitations of an NITC CSE education and how to succeed in the field despite them?</li>\r\n														<li>If I am happy with my life with a degree in computer science?</li>\r\n													</ol>\r\n													<p>Observations:</p>\r\n													<ol>\r\n														<li>\r\n															<p>The majority of questions (&gt;50%) related to the above three.</p>\r\n														</li>\r\n														<li>\r\n															<p>The following two stood out as particularly thoughtful questions:</p>\r\n															<blockquote>\r\n																<p>The limit of the heights you can reach. For someone aspiring to reach the top, say the CEO of Google or so, would a degree from NITC be a bit of a let down (it is not an IIT, hence no similar levels of exposure and opportunity, which cumulates\r\n																	up. You don’t get a good research internship / good recommendation =&gt; no good university for MS =&gt; not a nice position for a job to start with, etc)?</p>\r\n															</blockquote>\r\n															<p>and</p>\r\n															<blockquote>\r\n																<p>What are the benefits of Open Source contribution experience in Industry? I know that competitive programming helps one in making data structures and algorithms concepts stronger, but open source development also teaches one how to read\r\n																	and maintain large code bases, which is an important skill in the industry. Then why, in the placement procedure and many other activities, is competitive programming given much more importance over Open Source contribution?</p>\r\n															</blockquote>\r\n														</li>\r\n														<li>\r\n															<p>There was just one question about the age old debate on the importance of GPA.</p>\r\n														</li>\r\n														<li>\r\n															<p>I was happy to see that NITC has not lost its sense of humor as one of the questions was: <q>Will you marry me?</q></p>\r\n														</li>\r\n													</ol>\r\n													<p>I am not an authority on any of these questions (perhaps except the last one (-:) and am still trying to figure out answers to most of these myself. I decided a more useful approach would be to compare my present self as a graduate student\r\n														at Brown University and my past self from college.</p>\r\n													<p>I share my experience in the context of the questions raised. The aim is to leave the readers with some pointers that might be valuable in a wide range of career paths.</p>\r\n													<hr>\r\n													<h3><a id="Things_I_wish_I_knew_in_College_32"></a>Things I wish I knew in College</h3>\r\n													<dl>\r\n														<dt><a id="How_to_Learn_33"></a>How to Learn</dt>\r\n														<dd>\r\n															<p>\r\n																I spent two years in industry before going for a master’s degree. After being away from a traditional educational institution, it took me a whole semester to figure out how to learn effectively. How come my usual learning process, reliable enough to pass\r\n																any exam in college, was not working anymore? If I knew about <em><a href="https://www.coursera.org/learn/learning-how-to-learn">the science of learning</a></em> back in college, I would not have taken any pride in not\r\n																taking effective notes in classes or studying only a night before an exam. Neither would I have shied away from studying in groups and learning by teaching.</p>\r\n														</dd>\r\n														<dt><a id="Time_Management_and_Prioritization_37"></a>Time Management and Prioritization</dt>\r\n														<dd>\r\n															<p>Time is money and those who master it manage to climb the ladders of success. I learned how students here at Brown keep track of the time they spend on classes and assignments and take decisions scientifically based on their priorities\r\n																and schedule. In college, I had figured out how to juggle my life around my various roles (student, with CSEA, remote internship, lab administration, projects, TEDx, competitions), especially thanks to <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=blaK_tB_KQA">Randy Pausch’s advice</a>.\r\n																But I failed to do enough justice to some of them while being a perfectionist at others. I wish I then knew the meaning of <q>doing things right vs. doing the right things.</q></p>\r\n														</dd>\r\n													</dl>\r\n												</div>\r\n												<div class="col-md-6">\r\n													<dl>\r\n														<dt><a id="Importance_of_Reading_41"></a>Importance of Reading</dt>\r\n														<dd>\r\n															<p>If I were to list out each successful (for some criteria of success) person I have ever met, I doubt I will find any who said they were not a voracious reader. Be it books (fiction, non-fiction, other various genres) or technical literature\r\n																(textbooks, research papers, source code, technical blogs, etc), reading always stands out as a common factor in the people I come to admire. It took me first two years of college to realize I was not reading enough, which led me to take\r\n																up <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/challenges/3890-2016-reading-challenge">yearly reading challenges</a>. It took me another four years to be comfortable <a href="http://techglider.in/quote/2010/12/25/this-is-the-last-lecture-i-am-giving-you/">reading technical literature</a>.\r\n																I wish I had taken more time in college to learn and practice how to read effectively.\r\n															</p>\r\n														</dd><dt><a id="Importance_of_Writing_45"></a>Importance of Writing</dt>\r\n														<dd>\r\n															<p>Another common factor I find in most successful people is being able to communicate ideas effectively both in written and spoken form (it can be argued that former has more impact and lasting value for a CS professional). I practiced writing\r\n																consistently over my four years of college – either on <a href="http://techglider.in/post/">my blog</a>, lengthy email debates on FOSSCell mailing list, or those memos I wrote for my CSEA team. Having a public blog led to interesting discussions,\r\n																opportunities, and credibility boost. But, I wish I then knew the benefits of writing a private journal to introspect my day and plan ahead the next. It also helps to reflect back both on a short and long-term basis to figure out what\r\n																one wants to do with their life.\r\n															</p>\r\n														</dd><dt><a id="Coding_in_a_HighLevel_Language_49"></a>Coding in a High-Level Language</dt>\r\n														<dd>\r\n															<p>Though I knew some Python in college, I did not get to exercise it much during my time there. This was primarily because most of the curriculum is based on C and I did not work on many hobby projects. Department faculty take the stance\r\n																that teaching programming concepts in C helps students learn how things work at a lower level. Yet, I came to observe that <a href="http://cs.brown.edu/~ksinghal/post/java/">this inhibited my ability to think at a higher abstraction level</a>.\r\n																I wish I had spent more time learning either modern C++, Java, (advanced) Python or a functional programming language like Haskell. Knowing just C can severely limit one’s ability to solve problems and perform well in job interviews.</p>\r\n														</dd><dt><a id="How_to_Think_53"></a>How to Think</dt>\r\n														<dd>\r\n															<p>One of the primary goals of a college education is to teach one how to think for themselves. This not only involves using independent thought to work on projects and assignments but also learning to <a href="https://plus.google.com/+KartikSinghal/posts/FMCPbKXgetY">honestly accept your ignorance and ask questions</a>.\r\n																It was easy in college to get involved in groupthink or forget that my only real competition was with my past self. I wish I had taken <a href="http://techglider.in/quote/2011/03/06/i-am-free-no-matter-what-rules-surround/">full responsibility for my own education</a>																and not depended too much on the limitations of my alma mater.</p>\r\n														</dd>\r\n													</dl>\r\n													<p>One thing common to all the above skills and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metacognition">meta-skills</a> is that they take consistent practice and effort to develop (I am still continuously learning them). A college environment\r\n														provides a good combination of personal freedom, enough free time, necessary infrastructure, and a conducive learning ecosystem (with classes, teachers, and peers) that, in my opinion, it is just the right time to develop these skills. I\r\n														wish I knew this back then.</p>\r\n													<hr>\r\n													<p>I have deliberately left the questions raised in the survey unanswered in this article. But I will be happy to respond to original askers and to specific follow-up questions <a href="http://techglider.in/about/">over email</a>.</p>\r\n													<p style="font-style:italic;margin-top:1.2em;">Thanks to my friends Marilyn George, <a href="http://jaseemabid.github.io/">Jaseem Abid</a>, Lauren Bange, and <a href="http://pranavashok.name/">Pranav Ashok</a> for reading drafts of this article and providing valuable feedback.</p>\r\n												</div>\r\n											</div>\r\n										</div>\r\n									</div>\r\n								</div>\r\n								<!--containerfluid-->\r\n							</div>\r\n							<!--light div-->\r\n						</div>\r\n						<!--scroller-->\r\n					</div>\r\n					<!--content -->\r\n				</div>\r\n<!--bb-item-->'),
(32, 'CSEA Updates', 'Navaneeth Kishore', 3, 5, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item5">\r\n        <div class="pagenum white">\r\n            4/10\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class="content page" style="background-image:url(http://www.stcomputing.net/_include/img/slider-images/image01.jpg); background-size:cover">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n                .newul li{\r\n                list-style: disc outside none;\r\n                }\r\n\r\n                </style>\r\n                <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                    <div class="row">\r\n                        <h2>CSED Updates</h2>\r\n                        <hr>\r\n                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                            <ul class="newul">\r\n								<li>Dr. Saidalavi Kaladi recently took charge as Head of our Department. Team Threads wishes Saidalavi sir a good tenure :) </li>\r\n                                <li>The CSEA activities this academic year started with a mentor-ship program in which interested second year students were assigned mentors from third and fourth year students. The aim of this program was to connect second years with their seniors and also answer the many questions they have about the next three years of NITC life lying ahead of them.</li>\r\n                                <li>We organised a talk in which Mr. Suhail Rehman, a cloud and distributed computing researcher shared his experience on how the course on cloud is designed and taught at Carnegie Mellon University. The talk featured insights into the emerging topics in big data and cloud computing.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                            <ul class="newul">\r\n								<li>Department Onam was celebrated with unrivalled enthusiasm on Thursday, 22nd September...wasn''t it a sight to see. If you didn''t, there are some pics below!! </li>\r\n                                <li>To help the second years get started with Linux, a Linux boot camp was held as done every year. Students came with their laptops and volunteers helped them with installing and setting up the OS. Upon request of the participants, this was followed by a one day Linux Basics Workshop.</li>\r\n                                <li>A two day Pre-Tathva Workshop was conducted for B. Tech and MCA first years on Game Development using python. The participants were new to Python, and pygame module was used to introduce them to the language in a fun and interesting way.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n'),
(33, 'The Fork Not Taken', 'Anjana Soman', 3, 6, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item6">\r\n    <div class="pagenum"></div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>The Fork Not Taken</h2>\r\n\r\n            <p class="author">- <em>Anjana Soman, B. Tech. CSE 2014-2018 Batch</em></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h3> </h3>\r\n<p>The cores are whirring away in the back of my head, the clock cycles ticking steadily as I stand watching the ultimate embodiment of human choice – the innocent fork in the yellow brick road. If I could peer ahead, I would have seen the two paths wind away into the horizon, but alas, I wasn''t blessed with foresight. The Creator had deemed that I be a creature of the moment, tackling my life one line of fate at a time. </p>\r\n<p>I am an alchemist.</p>\r\n<p>My life is consumed by the task of converting ores into precious objects the cores employ to fulfill the tasks enlisted to our workforce. If you were to ask me, and you never will, I’d describe life as a series of remarkable events, just like the rest of humanity would. Some events are tougher on the nerves than others – oh to speak of the terrors I’ve seen! Many a time, I’ve walked the whole way to find that there is nowhere left to go and I stay stuck in limbo! All I can do then is to await divine intervention, for the masters of my fate to offer me yet another exception, a call to the higher powers, for a chance to start my life anew. But between these events though, I merely lie dormant, ruminating on the lessons and exceptions I’ve encountered in the recent past, learning from the endless errors I’ve encountered and fixed. </p>\r\n\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h4></h4>\r\n<p>Each event, no matter how short or long, complex or direct, quick or slow, brings me back to this fundamental battle of choice. Over my past instances, I’ve realized that one road will result in the repetition of the whole event, whilst the other is my way out to the next. The former I see, is worn out and ridden with potholes. I can see bugs crawling all over the edges, fault lines segmenting the oft-trodden road. It hits me with a strong sense of déjà vu; I am overwhelmed by the belief that some version of me, in another time, in another space, has taken this road, battling the demons popping up at every step.</p><p> And yet as I look at the other one, I know, despite my lack of foresight, that it is the way out of the infinite loop of detecting and fixing the errors my masters have created in their ignorance and oversight. No faults, no crawling bugs, no permission violations, no illegal activities await my perusal along this road. Just a quick and uninterrupted traversal to the end of the source, a hassle-free conversion to the final object. </p>\r\n<p>I may end up compiling mile-long strips of ore, using my skill and knowledge to allow my masters to create an object perfect in its execution. But as my life terminates at the end of the long run, as the workforce goes to sleep till the power returns, I shall look back upon this fork in the road. Amidst a deep sigh of 0s and 1s, I shall be telling my children, my threads, that I took the one less travelled by, and that has made all the difference.\r\n</p>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(34, 'Editorial', 'Aparna Jairaj', 3, 2, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item2">\r\n    <div class="pagenum">2/10</div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>Editorial</h2>\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h3>  </h3>\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h4></h4>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n<p>Welcome back to the third issue of Threads, the official Computer Science Department Newsletter. After a long break, we''re back in full swing, bringing you the Monsoon ''16 edition of Threads: Volume II Issue I- to keep you updated with the latest happenings in and around the department and the FOSS World, as well as a few comics and puzzles for you to mull over and enjoy.</p> \r\n<br/>\r\n<p>This edition features a few special articles. Firstly, we have an article written by a 2013 alumnus, Kartik Singhal, that sheds some light on the most popular and frequently asked questions and concerns raised by the CSE body in a poll taken recently. Read on to learn what to expect and what to be prepared for through his first-hand experience in the industry and in pursuing a graduate degree. Secondly, we have an interesting and highly informative article written by none other than the former secretary of CSEA (a 2016 alumnus), K Prasad Krishnan, titled "Big Data: The Hadoop way". </p> \r\n<br/>\r\n<p>Further, through this issue we attempt to pursue a whole new take on the art that is programming. Errors are necessarily evil. Or so we are accustomed to believe anyway. \r\nAs gratifying as it is to see the results of a hundred lines of code toiled over for, one has got to admit that nothing is as frustrating as a missing little semicolon, or a sneaky null reference somewhere in your code. Don''t miss out on the article "The Fork Not Taken", offering a unique perspective on this very predicament. \r\nSo the next time you get stuck with a compile time error, remember - "To err is human; to compile, divine".</p> \r\n<br/>\r\n<p>Until next time.</p> \r\n<br/>\r\n<div align="right"><p>- Team Threads</p></div>\r\n<br/>\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content --> \r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(36, 'Upcoming Coding Contests', 'Kumar Tej', 3, 8, '<div class="bb-item" id="item8">\r\n    <div class="pagenum"></div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>Upcoming coding contests</h2>\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h3>Practice Challenges</h3><br>\r\n                <ul>\r\n                    <li><strong>ACM ICPC Prepatory Series By Team Forthewatc</strong>h <a href="https://www.codechef.com/IPC15FLC">Codechef</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li><strong>Google Apac Test</strong> <a href="https://code.google.com/codejam/apactest/">Google</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>October Easy ''16 <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/october-easy-16/">Hackerearth</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>October Clash ''16 <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/october-clash-16/">Hackerearth</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>HourRank 13 <a href="https://www.hackerrank.com/contests/hourrank-13/challenges">Hackerrank</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>Week Of Code 24 <a href="https://www.hackerrank.com/contests/w24/challenges">Hackerrank</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>October Long Challenge 2016 <a href="https://www.codechef.com/OCT16">Codechef</a></li><br>\r\n                    <li>October Cook-Off 2016 <a href="http://www.codechef.com/COOK75">Codechef</a></li><br>\r\n                </ul>\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <h4>From Companies</h4><br>\r\n                    <ul>\r\n                        <li>Walmart Codesprint <a href="https://www.hackerrank.com/walmart-codesprint-algo">(Contest Link)</a></li><br><br>\r\n                        <li>Cognizant UI Developer Hiring Challenge <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/cognizant-ui-developer-hiring-challenge/">(Contest Link)</a></li><br><br>\r\n                        <li>Amazon SDE Hiring Challenge <a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/amazon-sde-hiring-challenge-1/">(Contest Link)</a></li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->'),
(37, 'Home', 'Aashish', 3, 1, '<div class="bb-item" id="item1"><div class="pagenum">1/13</div><div class="content page1" style="background-image:url(http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/27.jpg)"><div class="scroller" style="text-align:center"><div class="frontpage" style="background:rgba(0,0,0,.3);">        <h2 style="color:#fff">Threads</h2>        <div style="float:right"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/2.jpg" style="width:100px"/></div>        <p style="color:#fff">Volume II, Issue I September 2016</p>        <p style="color:#fff">Official Newsletter</p>        <p style="color:#fff">Department of Computer Science and Engineering</p>      </div></div></div></div>'),
(38, 'The Team', 'CSEA', 3, 12, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item12">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            11/11\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>The Team</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4 col-md-offset-3">\r\n                                <h4 class="team">Editors</h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ul class="special">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/aparna-jairaj-884751b1">Aparna Jairaj</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aashishsatya">Aashish Satyajith</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/pbhopalka">Piyush Bhopalka</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/kumar-tej-41297699">Kumar Tej</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/navaneeth-kishore-4b8832b5">Navaneeth Kishore</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/rachna-sasheendran-82122b110">Rachna Sasheendran</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/pavithra-a-varier-b58142110">Pavithra A Varier</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/anjanasoman">Anjana Soman</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="http://people.cse.nitc.ac.in/pathari/">Vinod Pathari</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4">\r\n                                <h4 class="team">Designers</h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ul class="special">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://github.com/anasanzari">Anas Ansari</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/nithin-jose-tom-72b025b3">Nithin Jose Tom</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4">\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-12">\r\n                                <div class="socialbuttons">\r\n                                    <a class="social" href="https://www.facebook.com/CSEA.NITC"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/5.jpg"></a> <a class="social" href="http://assoc.cse.nitc.ac.in"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/6.jpg"></a>\r\n                                </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="center">Suggestions for improvement are welcome.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="center">As always, we are accepting articles for our next issues. Please drop us a mail at <a href="mailto:csed.newsletter@gmail.com" target="_top">csed.newsletter@gmail.com</a></p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n');
