(39, 'Opportunities', 'Kumar', 3, 9, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item9">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            7/10\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>Opportunities Galore</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <ul class="blacktux">\r\n                                    <li>GATE Examination <a href="http://www.gate.iitr.ernet.in/">portal</a> will be open till 4<sup>th</sup> October 2016.\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>Applications are open for <a href="http://univ.tifr.res.in/gs2017/">TIFR''s PhD. Program</a>. Deadline is 10<sup>th</sup> October.\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>Applications for <a href="http://web-japps.ias.ac.in:8080/fellowship2016/">Summer Research Fellowshiop Programme (SRFP)</a> (at IITs, IISc etc) will be open till 30<sup>th</sup> November\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>IUSSTF launches <a href="http://www.iusstf.org/story/53-51-Viterbi-India-Program.html">Viterbi-India Program</a>. Apply by 15<sup>th</sup> November 2016.\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>IUSSTF hosts <a href="http://www.iusstf.org/story/53-51-Viterbi-India-Program.html">S.N. Bose Scholars Program</a>. Last Date for Application is 31<sup>st</sup> October 2016.\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>DAAD''s <a href="https://www.daad.de/deutschland/stipendium/datenbank/en/21148-scholarship-database/?daad=1&detail=50015295&origin=4&page=1&q=wise&status=1&subjectGrps=">Working Internship</a> has 1<sup>st</sup> November 2016 as deadline.\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>Also, don''t miss out on some amazing learning opportunities at a few startups.</li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <h3><strong>Featured</strong>\r\n                                </h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <h3>ACM ICPC</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <div class="img"><img src="https://icpc.baylor.edu/img/welcome/cm2-logo-panel_joel_wo_lang.png">\r\n                                </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <h4>ACM ICPC Online Contest on October 8<sup>th</sup>. Keep Track at <a href="https://icpc.baylor.edu/">ACM ICPC</a></h4>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n'),
(40, 'Big Data The Hadoop Way', 'KPK', 3, 7, '<style scoped>\r\nol{\r\n  margin-left:50px;\r\n}\r\nol li {\r\n  font-size: 1.0em;\r\n  line-height: 1.0;\r\n  font-weight: 300;\r\n  padding: 5px 5px;\r\n  text-align: justify;\r\n}\r\n</style>\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item7">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            8/11\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content page3">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-xs-8">\r\n                                <h3 style="text-align:right">Big Data The Hadoop Way</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p style="text-align:right">- <em><a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/prasad-krishnan-954a61108">K Prasad Krishnan</a>, B. Tech CSE Batch of 2012 - 2016</em></p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-xs-4"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/28.jpg" style="width:200px;max-width:100%">\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p>We have seen instances of several technological events taking the computer science industry by storm like the World Wide Web in the early 90''s and the entry of smart phones in 2005 that multiplied the number of Internet users by a huge factor. Over the past few years from 2006, Hadoop, the big data technology has been making its presence felt in the industry with the various companies including Facebook, Google and Yahoo adopting it and more and more companies trying to.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>So, what is this Hadoop anyway? According to Wikipedia, Hadoop is an open-source software framework written in Java for distributed storage and distributed processing of very large data sets on computer clusters built from commodity hardware. Inspite of the presence of Distributed computing since decades, yet Hadoop was able to make a difference in the industry. It is different from the traditional distributed computing technologies and simplified parallel programming greatly. Anyone with enough programming knowledge could now write a simple Map Reduce program in any programming knowledge blissfully unaware that it will be running in parallel in Hadoop.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>The amount of data generated in the Web today is enormous. The hard disk drives(to store data) have become cheaper but to process the data to the tunes of petabytes and terabytes efficiently is still a challenge. Hadoop comes with an answer with its HDFS, a file system to store data and Map Reduce, its data analysis engine. Hadoop is designed for batch processing or near real time processing(as it is often called) and not for applications requiring real time processing for which traditional RDBMSs would fare better. Even that is changing now as a new project called Apache Spark is promising to have processing speed 10x to 100x times faster than the Map Reduce framework and thus, the number of Spark users is increasing day by day.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Hadoop was created by Doug Cutting in 2005. Initially created for a project called Nutch, a search engine, it was when Cutting moved into Yahoo in 2005 that he could work with a dedicated team on Hadoop. Cutting named Hadoop after his son''s toy elephant. In 2008, a 910-node Yahoo cluster sorted one terabyte in 209 seconds with 1000 lines of Java code beating the previous winner by over 1 minute (see <a href="http://sortbenchmark.org">sortbenchmark.org</a>).</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <p>Hadoop mainly consists of two components, HDFS(Hadoop Distributed File System) to store the huge data sets(in the scale of terabytes and petabytes) and the Map Reduce engine to process the data sets. Hadoop mainly stresses on "scale out" rather than "scale up" i.e use more of commodity hardware rather than increasing the processing power of existing hardware. The Hadoop cluster consists of a NameNode(master) which stores the metadata about the files in the cluster and sevaral DataNodes where the actual data resides, in block size of 64 MB (typically). And it provides a replication factor of 3 (default) meaning, at an instance 3 copies of file exists. It is quite easy to manipulate files in HDFS as various commands(like the common Linux commands we are familiar with) are available.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>The Map Reduce program consists of two parts- a Mapper and a Reducer. A Mapper maps a set of key-value pairs to another set(possibly different) of key-value pairs. Then, keys are sorted and a key and its corresponding values is fed as input to the Reducer which produces another set of key-value pairs as output. Although initially it would seem difficult to write programs suited to this framework, almost all programs can be worked out to be written in this "MapReduce" way. The Map Reduce engine consists of a central JobTracker (similiar to NameNode in HDFS) to which the client submits the Map Reduce job. It then splits the job to different tasks and assigns it to different TaskTrackers(similiar to DataNodes in HDFS). Although Java is generally used to write MapReduce programs, with a utility called Hadoop Streaming, it is possible to write the mapper and reducer programs in any programming language(even shell scripts).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Along with Hadoop there are several different projects built in and around Hadoop like:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ol type="i">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://hive.apache.org/">Hive</a>, a data warehouse infrastructure,\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="http://hbase.apache.org/">HBase</a>, a distributed, versioned, non-relational database,\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="http://oozie.apache.org/">Oozie</a>, a workflow scheduler,\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://sqoop.apache.org/docs/1.4.6/SqoopUserGuide.html">Sqoop</a>, a tool for transferring data between relational databases and Hadoop,\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>etc.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p>Though many fear that Hadoop has already passed its peak, the ever evolving projects in the Hadoop ecosystem is a proof that this technology is here to stay. A recent study even showed that Bengaluru is next only to Silicon Valley in terms of number people with skills in Hadoop and its ecosystem components. (For more info, refer: <a href="https://hadoop.apache.org/">hadoop.apache.org</a>, <a href="http://www.cloudera.com/content/cloudera/en/about/hadoop-and-big-data.html">Hadoop: The Definitive Guide by Tom White)</a></p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n'),
(41, 'Obituary', 'Team CSEA', 3, 3, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item3">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n            2/10\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>Obituary</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <h3>\r\n                                </h3>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                <h4>\r\n                                </h4>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                    <!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        <p style="text-align:center">\r\n            <img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/33.jpg" />\r\n        </p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p>With deep shock and profound sorrow, we record the sad and untimely demise of Ms. Geethu Mohan, our former student of M.Tech (CSE- Information Security) belonging to the 2011-‘13 batch. Ms. Geethu breathed her last on 23rd September 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p>Ms. Geethu was an excellent student with extremely good caliber and behavior. Her relentless quest for excellence was commendable. She was serving as an Assistant Professor of Computer Science and Engineering at Amrita University, Coimbatore.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p>The faculty, staff, students and alumni of the Department of Computer Science and Engineering, National Institute of Technology Calicut, deeply mourn the sad and sudden demise of Ms. Geethu and express our heart-felt condolences to her bereaved parents, family members and friends.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p>We sincerely pray to the Almighty for her eternal peace.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <p>The entire CSED family joins Geethu’s parents, relatives and friends in sharing their grief at this moment of irreparable loss. May the Almighty give them the strength and courage to bear this terrible blow.</p>\r\n                    <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div align="right">\r\n                        <p>- Team Threads</p>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                    <br>\r\n                </div>\r\n                <!--light div-->\r\n            </div>\r\n            <!--scroller-->\r\n        </div>\r\n        <!--content -->\r\n    </div>\r\n    <!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(42, 'CSED Updates', 'Nithin Jose Tom', 4, 6, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item6">\r\n		<div class="pagenum white">\r\n			7/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content page" style="background-image:url(https://telecomtalk.info/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/india-mobile-internet.png); background-size:cover">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n				                                                .newul li{\r\n				                                                list-style: disc outside none;\r\n				                                                }\r\n\r\n				</style>\r\n\r\n				<div class="container-fluid">\r\n					<div class="row">\r\n						<h2>CSED Updates</h2>\r\n\r\n						<hr>\r\n\r\n\r\n						<div class="col-md-6">\r\n							<ul class="newul">\r\n								<li>''Loopback'', an alumni meet that focused on the 2007 graduates was conducted and included activities like treasure hunt, games and cultural programmes.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<li>A weekly program called ''Coding with Seniors'' was launched to help students gain experience tackling programming problems commonly asked during company recruitment interviews.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<li>Prabhav Adhikari, Mandava Jaya Krishna and Raghu Pavan participated in India Finals of ACM-ICPC 2017. Congrats to the team!</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<li>Sessions on C and C++ were conducted by the new second year executives for the benefit of the first years.</li>\r\n							</ul>\r\n						</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n						<div class="col-md-6">\r\n							<ul class="newul">\r\n								<li>A workshop on Selenium, the automated testing framework was conducted by Saksham Agarwal and team. The audience included first year MCAs and first and second year B. Tech students.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<li>School FOSSMeet was conducted by FOSSCell to introduce school children to the world of FOSS on February 18th.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<li>Piyush Bhopalka conducted a talk on Introduction to TensorFlow as a part of Google Developer''s Group series of talks on February 19th.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<li>A study group was formed for helping students with the online course <a href="https://www.coursera.org/learn/build-a-computer">''From NAND to Tetris''</a> during the holidays.\r\n								</li>\r\n							</ul>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n				</div>\r\n			</div>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(43, 'Why Competitors Open Stores Right Next To Each Oth', 'Aashish Satyajith', 4, 4, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item4">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			4/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content page2">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<h3>Why Competitors Open Stores Right Next to Each Other</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p class="author">- <em><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/aashishsatya">Aashish Satyajith</a>, B. Tech CSE Batch of 2017</em></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<p>There''s this road in my home town Thrissur called Palace Road, the peculiarity of the road being that two clothing behemoths - Kalyan Silks and Pulimootil Silks - have set up their stores right next to each other!! I passionately try to avoid these places because every time I go shopping there with my cousins, they go to one store first, decide there''s not enough selection and go immediately to the other store, and I have no choice but to tag along with them (no offence to the shopping enthusiasts out there).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>This also doesn''t make sense from an business point of view - why on earth would you go set up a store right under an established competitor''s nose? Wouldn''t it have been more profitable to set it somewhere where there ISN''T such a store available, so that you get more people and hence more profits?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>And the surprising fact is that this isn''t exclusive to just clothing stores, there are plenty of other such examples in the real world (this might also be very relatable):</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/34.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>These examples defy logic. Or do they? Let''s have a look.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Imagine there''s a beach (there''s no need to imagine anything else) and there are children playing on the beach. You''re an ice-cream seller, and fortunately, you happen to be the first ice-cream seller along that part of the beach. Where would you set up your store? Basically you could''ve set up your store anywhere along the beach, and those who are in dire need of an ice-cream would have come to you anyway because you''re the only ice-cream seller on that beach. But since you''re such a nice guy/gal, you decide to set up shop at the centre of the beach so that the maximum distance that people will have to walk is limited to half a mile:</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/35.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<p>The plan works out well, business is booming, you''re happy, your customers are happy. So far, so good.</p>\r\n								\r\n								<p>But not for long.</p>\r\n\r\n								<p>Enter Ted, your arch-enemy, who also happens to be selling the exact same product as you are!! Not wanting to make a scene, you both decide to occupy different sections of the beach so as to serve different customers. The chosen positions are also optimal in the sense that now the maximum distance a customer has to walk is a quarter mile, and not half a mile as earlier:\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/36.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Even then, things are going fine. Until your arch-enemy decides to reveal his true self, and sets up shop right at the centre and gains the upper hand:</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/37.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n								\r\n								<p>That jerk!! It''s time for payback. We come up with the following plan - we''ll rise and shine a little earlier than usual the next day and set up shop in such a way that we get 75% of the market share and he''s left with the rest:</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/38.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n								\r\n							</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">								\r\n\r\n								<p>The clever reader will already have realized the flaw in our plan: he can set up shop a few paces away from us and coolly recapture his share of the market:</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/39.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n								\r\n								<p>Damn, we underestimated him.</p>\r\n\r\n								<p>But no, we have no intention of losing that easily. At the next opportunity, WE move ten paces from him so as to gain the upper hand:</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/40.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<p>But then, he isn''t to be taken lightly either. He moves his shop a few paces from us at his next opportunity, just like we did. This to-and-to motion continues until both the sellers end up at the exact centre of the beach:</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/41.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<p>And so there you go -- shops eventually get set up close to each other, even if it doesn''t seem to make sense business-wise. This is called <b>Hoteling''s model of spatial simulation</b> in the literature, if you''re into these kinds of things.</p>\r\n								\r\n								<p>There are a few more things worthy of note here. This kind of a situation where nobody has any incentive to shift from his or her strategy is termed in economics and game theory as a Nash equilibrium. (Yep, that''s the same Nash you saw in the famous movie <i>A Beautiful Mind</i>). The movement towards the centre happened because the initial position that we and Ted had set up in was not a Nash equilibrium -- any of us could have tried shifting a little bit towards the centre to gain the upper hand (like Ted did):</p>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/42.jpg">\r\n								</div>\r\n								\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n								<p>This is also a classic example of how a Nash equilibrium might not lead to a globally optimal outcome. Notice now that in the worst case, a customer who wants ice-cream will have to walk half a mile as opposed to the quarter mile she only would have had to walk when both the sellers set up shops in their original positions.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>...and that''s one explanation of why shops of the same kind tend to cluster. Philosophically speaking, I like to think of this as the mathematical explanation behind the time-tested statement "Keep your enemies close" ;-)</p>\r\n								\r\n								<p>Hope you enjoyed this exposure to some aspects of game theory. It''s a fascinating subject, and is full of such examples.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><i>P. S. Although this is a pretty standard example in economics and game theory, images have been blatantly copied from <a href="http://ed.ted.com/lessons/why-do-competitors-open-their-stores-next-to-one-another-jac-de-haan">here</a>. But since they''re nice people at TED (and have left the video free to be used non-commercially), they won''t sue us.</i></p>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n				</div>\r\n			</div>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>\r\n'),
(44, 'Upcoming Coding Contests', 'Kumar Tej', 4, 10, '<div class="bb-item" id="item10">\r\n  <div class="pagenum">10/13</div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n        <div class="scroller">\r\n            <div class="light">\r\n                <h2>Upcoming Coding Contests</h2>\r\n                <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                  <div class="row">\r\n                        <div class="col-md-6"> \r\n                            <ul class="whitetux">\r\n                              <li><a href="https://code.google.com/codejam/kickstart">Kickstart 2017</a></li><br/>\r\n                              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/62.jpg"/></div><br/> \r\n                              <li><a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/challenge/competitive/march-clash-17/">March Clash ''17</a></li><br/>\r\n                              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/69.jpg"/></div><br/>\r\n                              <li><a href="https://www.hackerrank.com/hourrank-18">HourRank 18</a></li><br/>\r\n                              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/58.jpg"/></div><br/>                              \r\n                            </ul> \r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                            <ul class="whitetux">\r\n                              <li><a href="https://www.codechef.com/MARCH17">March Challenge 2017</a></li><br/>\r\n                              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/45.jpg"/></div><br/>\r\n                              <li><a href="https://code.google.com/codejam/">Google Code Jam 2017</a></li><br/>\r\n                              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/65.jpg"/></div><br/>\r\n                              <li><a href="https://www.hackerearth.com/challenge/competitive/march-easy-17/">March Easy ''17</a></li><br/>\r\n                              <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/70.jpg"/></div><br/>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div> \r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>'),
(45, 'Opportunities', 'Bhava', 4, 10, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item9">\r\n    <div class="pagenum">11/13</div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>Opportunities</h2>\r\n\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <ul class="blacktux">\r\n                                    <li>Applications for <b>Charpak - Research Internship Program 2017 </b> are open. <a hreaf="http://www.inde.campusfrance.org/sites/locaux/files/inde/imce/Application_Form_Research%20Internship_Program.doc">Click</a> to download the application form. For more details visit <a href="http://www.inde.campusfrance.org/en/page/charpak-research-internship-program">here</a><br>Deadline : March 2017</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\nThe <b> California Institute of Technology</b> is inviting applications for Caltech - SURF Program. </br> Click <a href="https://sfponline.caltech.edu/index.cfm?event=view.HomePage&p=Home">here</a> to apply. You can also check for the list of available projects <a href="http://announcements.surf.caltech.edu/index.cfm?event=ShowAOPublicList&inFrame=&type=SURF&formType=AO_CIT">here</a>.<br> Deadline : 22<sup>nd</sup> February 2017.\r\n</li> <br>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\nApply for <b>NCTU Taiwan''s Internship Program</b> <a href="http://www.ia.nctu.edu.tw/files/13-1000-781.php?Lang=en">here</a>. It''s open only for Masters and PhD students.\r\n</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\nApplications for <b>Industrial Technology Research Institute </b>(ITRI) ''s Summer Internship will close at the end of February. To learn more about it, Click <a href="https://www.itri.org.tw/eng/Content/Messagess/contents.aspx?&SiteID=1&MmmID=617731531432246346&MSID=617766563745123512"> here</a>.\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n<ul class="blacktux">\r\n    <li>\r\n        Applications are now closed for <b>CERN openlab Summer Student Programme</b>.<br> But you can watch the lecture series prepared by the experts at CERN for students <a href="http://openlab.cern/summer-students-lectures">here</a>.        \r\n    </li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<a href="https://www.imsc.res.in/visiting_summer_student_program">The Institute of Mathematical Sciences</a> (IMSc) is accepting applications for their summer research program. <br>Follow the link above to apply. <br> Deadline is 28<sup>th</sup> February.\r\n</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n    Don''t forget to prepare for the <b>Google Summer of Code</b>. <br>\r\n    Take a look at <a href="https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/archive/2016/">2016 projects</a>.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n'),
(46, 'FUNtastic', 'Pavithra', 4, 12, '<div class="bb-item" id="item12">\r\n                    <div class="pagenum">\r\n                        13/13\r\n                    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="content">\r\n                        <div class="scroller">\r\n                            <div class="light">\r\n                                <h2>FUNtastic</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                                    <div class="row">\r\n                                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                                            <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/43.jpg">\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div class="col-md-6">\r\n\r\n                                            <div class="img"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/44.jpg">\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    </div>\r\n<p><i>(These files are from <a href="http://cloudtweaks.com/">cloudtweaks.com</a> and the Geek&Poke series.)</i>\r\n                                </p>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <!-- row-->\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <!--containerfluid-->\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <!--light div-->\r\n                    </div>\r\n                    <!--scroller-->\r\n                </div>\r\n                <!--content -->'),
(47, 'The Puzzler', 'Rachna', 4, 11, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item11">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			12/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<h2><b>The Puzzler</b><img alt="image1" src="http://www.clipartbest.com/cliparts/LiK/d4G/LiKd4GaRT.png">\r\n					</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<h3><b>Puzzle 1</b>\r\n								</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>During the age of the medieval empires, when knights and barbarians fought against each other, a man was captured and sentenced to death for allegedly befriending barbarians. The king, however, wanted to give him another chance. The king ordered him to his presence and asked him to choose one of the three knights present.<br>\r\n								<br>\r\n								One of the knights is the Knight of Life, and he always tells the truth. The second Knight is the Knight of Death, and he always tells lies. The third knight is the Knight of the Dungeon. He sometimes lies and sometimes tells the truth.<br>\r\n								<br>\r\n								If the man chooses the Knight of Death, he is to be executed before sunset. If he chooses the Knight of Life, he would be acquitted and set free right away. If he chooses the Knight of the Dungeon, he would spend the rest of his life imprisoned in the Dungeon.<br>\r\n								<br>\r\n								This is the first time the man ever saw these knights and could not recognize them. However, the man is allowed to ask these three knights one question each. Thus, the man asked the red-haired knight, "What is the name of this blond hair knight?" The reply was "He is the Knight of the Life." He asked the black-haired knight, "What is the name of this blond-haired knight?" The reply was "He is the Knight of Death." Then he asked the blond-haired knight "Who are you?" "I am the Knight of the Dungeon" was the reply. Luckily, the man was able to correctly choose the Knight of Life, and was set free immediately. Can you identify who the Knight of Life was, and also who the other two knights were?<br>\r\n								<br>\r\n								Solution to this puzzle can be found <a href="http://www.logicville.com">over here</a>.</p>\r\n							</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<h3><b>Puzzle 2</b>\r\n								</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>In the middle of the confounded desert, there is the lost city of “Ash”. To reach it, you will have to travel over land by foot from the coast. On a trek like this, each person can only carry enough rations for five days and the farthest we can travel in one day is 30 miles. Also, the city is 120 miles from the starting point. What is the fewest number of persons, including yourself, that you will need in your group so that you can reach the city, stay overnight, and then return to the coast without running out of supplies? How many persons (including yourself) will you need to accomplish this mission?</p>\r\n								<br>\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<h3><b>Puzzle 3</b>\r\n								</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Mr John has 25 horses, and he wants to pick the fastest 3 horses out of those 25. He has only 5 tracks, which means only 5 horses can run at a time. Assume he doesn’t have a stop watch. What is the minimum number of races required to find the 3 fastest horses?<br>\r\n								<br>\r\n								Solutions to puzzles 2 and 3 can be found <a href="http://puzzlefry.com/puzzles">over here</a>.</p>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n					<!--containerfluid-->\r\n				</div>\r\n				<!--light div-->\r\n			</div>\r\n			<!--scroller-->\r\n		</div>\r\n		<!--content -->\r\n	</div>\r\n	<!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(48, 'Social Networks: Studying People on the Edge', 'Pratik Banerjee', 4, 5, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item5">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">5/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<h3>Social Networks: Studying People on the Edge</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p class="author">- <em>Pratik Banerjee, M.Tech CSE Batch of 2017</em></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<p>Web traffic to facebook.com is ranked globally as the 3rd highest by Alexa Internet. While we are all guilty of spending sizeable portions of our time daily on the online social networking sites like Facebook and Twitter, the availability of such enormous amounts of data about the activities and interactions among people is allowing research into the social structures by graph theoretic means.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>In simple words, Social Network Analysis (SNA) is the analysis of networked structure of interactions between actors (most commonly, people) by putting the entities as nodes and the interactions (or ties) between them as edges on a graph. The goal behind all of this is to look for information present in the network properties that are not apparent before visualising them as graphs. Once it is made to a graph, we can estimate various parameters of the network such as degree distribution of the nodes, the average shortest path lengths, the clustering coefficients and community structures; and these parameters help us in characterizing the network.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Now, real-world social interactions more often than not have some well-studied properties that hold even across networks from different domains. One such property is that the networks which are mostly sparse and exhibit a Small-world network property which says that even if most nodes are not neighbours of one another, most nodes can be reached from every other node by a very small number of edges. In the early 20th century, a widely popular notion ''Six degrees of separation'' came up that suggested all living people in the world in just six or fewer steps away from each other by a chains of acquaintances. While that essentially rephrased the Small-world property, there was a recent study at Cornell [1] that uses the entire Facebook network of about 721 million active users and 69 billion friendship links and observes the average distance to be just 4.74; the world is indeed smaller than we think it is.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>SNA can be a prove to be a powerful tool in a variety of applications. One such area of application is in effective information spread in a network or marketing. Suppose you want to announce the launch of your new product to the people such that the information reaches everyone and quickly. If you know about the patterns of interaction among the people, how they interact and their degree of <i>relatedness</i>, you can potentially use that intelligence to pick out the <i>influential</i> people in the network, so that you target them with the information and it cascades fast and well to (most of) the population in minimum hops or time thereby reducing your cost or effort of marketing. A very similar approach is taken in SNAzzy (Social Network Analysis for Telecom Business Intelligence) for analysis of social networks created by "who-calls-whom" calling patterns of customers of Telecom Service Providers. By doing so, several insights about community structures, targets for campaigning of products and relative <i>importance</i> in the network are estimated.</p>\r\n							</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<p>Apart from marketing, SNA makes way for a detailed study of organised crimes such as terrorism, drug-trafficking and money laundering. Since it is a given fact that criminals make their group(s) of communication and coordination for their activities, intelligence using SNA tools is of help to track criminals. Interesting to note that, Saddam Hussein’s capture was in fact facilitated by SNA. Then Valdis Krebs manually constructed a terrorist network comprising the 19 hijackers involved in the 9/11 attacks [2]. The network was constructed from information about relationships among the hijackers from publicly released data from major newspapers; from the association matrix to integrate these relations, he drew the network showing possible patterns of association.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><img alt="The Terrorist Network surrounding 19 hijackers on Sep 11, 2001" src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/49.jpg" style="width:100%">\r\n								</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<center>\r\n									<small>The Terrorist Network surrounding 19 hijackers on Sep 11, 2001</small>\r\n								</center>\r\n								<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>After such visualisation, structural analysis is done on the graph to offer further intelligence about structural motifs and patterns in the network.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Since Social Network Analysis originates from social science research as a set of analytical tools that could map the members, their relationships, and patterns of collaboration, the possible application areas of the same is numerous and varied.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>There goes my two cents of an introduction and motivation to read up further about SNA.</p>\r\n\r\n								<hr>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>[1] “Four Degrees of Separation” by Lars Backstrom, Paolo Boldi, Marco Rosa, Johan Ugander, Sebastiano Vigna. Cornell University Library (2012), https://arxiv.org/abs/1111.4570v3<br>\r\n								[2] “Mapping Networks of Terrorist Cells” by V.E. Krebs. Connections 24(3), 43-52 (2001), http://www.orgnet.com/MappingTerroristNetworks.pdf</p>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n					<!--containerfluid-->\r\n				</div>\r\n				<!--light div-->\r\n			</div>\r\n			<!--scroller-->\r\n		</div>\r\n		<!--content -->\r\n	</div>\r\n	<!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `name`, `author`, `edition`, `number`, `content`) VALUES
(49, 'Women in STEM', 'Nikita Mathew', 4, 3, '\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item3">\r\n\r\n    <style scoped>\r\na {\r\ncolor:#4888EF;\r\n}\r\na:hover{\r\ncolor:#3B5998;\r\n}\r\n</style>\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			3/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content page3">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							<div class="col-xs-8">\r\n								<h3 style="text-align:right">Women in STEM</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p style="text-align:right">- <em><a href="http://people.cse.nitc.ac.in/nikita/">Nikita Mathew,</a> B. Tech CSE Batch of 2014</em></p>\r\n							</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-xs-4"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/50.jpg" style="width:200px;max-width:100%">\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<p>It’s a pleasure to be connecting back to Alma Mater. When I pondered on what topic I should write about in the alumnus column of the CSEA newsletter, I was perplexed. I thought about the technologies I have been working on like NoSQL DB, Ruby on Rails or Lambdas in Java which are fun and are trending. But there is one topic that I have come to understand and realize in the last 2 years after college and I think is my responsibility to share, which is something unique that I can talk about or contribute to - Women in STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics). This is specially for the young women in our college and all the young men who have women in their life ;-)</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Out of the total workforce in STEM, only 14% are women, according to the&nbsp;US Congressional Joint Economic Committee<sup><a href="http://www.esa.doc.gov/sites/default/files/womeninstemagaptoinnovation8311.pdf">[1]</a></sup>. Is it because women generally don’t have the aptitude required for mathematics or calculations? But when I think about it, I have several examples to counter the theory. Did you know that the world’s first programmer is a woman - <a href="http://www.computerhistory.org/babbage/adalovelace/">Ada Lovelace</a>? Did you know that <a href="http://physicsgirl.com/">Sabrina Pasterski</a> - who is just 22, has Stephen Hawking citing her papers!? There have been extensive studies in this area and the major attributes that contribute to this phenomenon are lack of exposure to the area in the early days, and even if they had opportunities to explore these areas, being a homemaker becomes the primary responsibility, and without a good support system, women drop out of these areas.&nbsp; There are many possible factors contributing to the discrepancy of women and men in STEM jobs, including: a lack of female role models, gender stereotyping, and less family-friendly flexibility in the STEM fields.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><b>Where are we headed to?</b>\r\n								</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>The world has become a global village. With mobile phones and internet becoming a necessary good like food, clothing and shelter, businesses reach a diverse audience. To deliver products and services that appeal to the diverse customer base, employers are giving due importance to diversity in their employee base. After all, putting oneself in the customer’s shoes and developing a product is of utmost importance for global enterprises.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><i>"If people think alike, then no matter how smart they are they most likely will get stuck at the same locally optimal solutions. Finding new and better solutions, innovating, requires thinking differently. That’s why diversity powers innovation."</i>\r\n								</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p style="text-align:right"><i>– Scott Page, The Difference, 2007</i>\r\n								</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><i>"One of the things that I really strongly believe in is that we need to have more girls interested in math, science, and engineering. We’ve got half the population that is way under-represented in those fields and that means that we’ve got a whole bunch of talent…not being encouraged the way they need to."</i>\r\n								</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p style="text-align:right"><i>- President Barack Obama, February 2013</i>\r\n								</p>\r\n							</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<p>Corporates have made studies and experiments and statistics say -</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<ol>\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p>According to the Atlantic Monthly magazine''s cover story in May, "Half a dozen global studies, conducted by the likes of Goldman Sachs and Columbia University, have found that companies employing women in large numbers outperform their competitors on every measure of profitability."</p>\r\n									</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p><b>Improved Operational and Financial Performance</b>: Women have tremendous purchasing power. Organizations who employ more women in key roles are better equipped to meet the needs of the broader market, because women know what women want<sup><a href="http://cdn.anitaborg.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/The-Case-for-Investing-in-Women-314.pdf?_ga=1.156962611.922126644.1484242747">[2]</a></sup>.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n										<p>\r\n										</p>\r\n									</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p><b>Increased Innovation</b>: For many companies, innovation is a strategic imperative. Research shows that women bring valuable perspectives and approaches to the ideation process, resulting in more innovative solutions to complex problems<sup><a href="http://cdn.anitaborg.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/The-Case-for-Investing-in-Women-314.pdf?_ga=1.156962611.922126644.1484242747">[2]</a></sup>.</p>\r\n									</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p><b>Better Problem Solving and Group Performance<sup><a href="http://cdn.anitaborg.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/The-Case-for-Investing-in-Women-314.pdf?_ga=1.156962611.922126644.1484242747">[2]</a></sup></b>: Knowledge work is performed in teams. Studies show that diverse groups solve problems more effectively than homogenous ones, raising overall performance and giving teams that include women a distinct competitive edge.</p>\r\n									</li>\r\n								</ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><a href="http://ghcindia.anitaborg.org/ghci-2016-student-career-fair/">The Grace Hopper Conference</a> held annually in the US and in India is one of the initiatives to gather corporates, leaders and women from schools, colleges and companies to learn new areas, explore new opportunities and encourage women. I would encourage all of you to find out more and participate in one of the conferences.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>Many companies&nbsp;have initiatives to partner with colleges and mentor young women who want to pursue their dreams in STEM. I personally know of one such initiative in Amazon and have heard and read about similar initiatives taken up by many companies.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p><b>What can we do?</b>\r\n								</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<ol>\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p>As NITCians, it should be easy for us to&nbsp;introduce/inculcate science and technology in our families. This is to eliminate the root cause of lack of exposure.</p>\r\n									</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p>Girls:</p>\r\n                                                                \r\n											<p>Learn by doing. Inculcate a coding culture. Take your lab sessions seriously. It''s the time where you can build software by applying what you have learnt!</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n											<p>Take up mini projects. Ask our teachers for guidance. Their mentorship is a treasure! MOOCs are a good place too. Coursera, Udacity, PluralSight,etc have a range of courses each accompanied with a project.</p>\r\n										</li>\r\n									\r\n\r\n									<li>\r\n										<p>Guys - you are strong enough to be the support system that women in your life need. Today she maybe your mother or sister or classmate, and tomorrow your wife or daughter or colleague.</p>\r\n									</li>\r\n								</ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<p>References:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n								<ul style="font-size:.6em">\r\n									<li>[1] <a href="http://www.esa.doc.gov/sites/default/files/womeninstemagaptoinnovation8311.pdf">Statistics: Women in STEM, A Gender Gap To Innovation, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Department of Commerce</a>\r\n									</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n									<li>[2] <a href="http://cdn.anitaborg.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/The-Case-for-Investing-in-Women-314.pdf?_ga=1.156962611.922126644.1484242747">Innovation By Design: The Case for Investing in Women, Anita Borg Institute</a>\r\n									</li>\r\n								</ul>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n				</div>\r\n			</div>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n'),
(50, 'Editorial', 'Aparna', 4, 2, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item2">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			2/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<h2>Editorial</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<h3>\r\n								</h3>\r\n							</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-6">\r\n								<h4>\r\n								</h4>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n					<!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p>Greetings from Team Threads!</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p>We''re very pleased to announce the fourth issue of Threads (yes, it''s that time of the semester again!!). We''re back with our brain teasers, light humour and department updates. Keep your eyes out for the upcoming coding contests we''ve listed too. We hope you enjoy this edition as much as we did putting it together.</p>\r\n					<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p>In this issue, we have quite the variety of articles. First, we have an article by Aashish Satyajith - "Why Competitors Open Stores Right Next to Each Other", a simple game theoretic concept not many of us might know. Chances are, you may have wondered about the same at some point. It will all make sense after this, trust me.</p>\r\n					<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p>We have another interesting article by Pratik Banerjee about Social Network analysis. Read on to find out how small the world really is.</p>\r\n					<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p>Finally, as per tradition, we have an article in our alumni corner - "Women in STEM". A huge shout-out to Nikita Mathew from the 2014 batch. Thank you for the article and for being an inspiration to the rest of the Women in STEM.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p>Happy reading! And until next time!</p>\r\n					<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div align="right">\r\n						<p>- Team Threads</p>\r\n					</div>\r\n					<br>\r\n				</div>\r\n				<!--light div-->\r\n			</div>\r\n			<!--scroller-->\r\n		</div>\r\n		<!--content -->\r\n	</div>\r\n	<!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>\r\n'),
(51, 'Home', 'Anas', 4, 1, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item1">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			1/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content page1" style="background-image:url(http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/51.jpg)">\r\n			<div class="scroller" style="text-align:center">\r\n				<div class="frontpage" style="background:rgba(0,0,0,.3);">\r\n					<h2 style="color:#fff">Threads</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div style="float:right"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/2.jpg" style="width:100px">\r\n					</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p style="color:#fff">Volume II, Issue II January 2017</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p style="color:#fff">Official Newsletter</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<p style="color:#fff">Department of Computer Science and Engineering</p>\r\n				</div>\r\n			</div>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(52, 'CSED Teaser', 'Anas', 4, 7, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item7">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			8/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<h2>CSED Teaser</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							The CSED recently put out a teaser trailer for its documentary that is due soon. Watch and enjoy!\r\n\r\n							<p>\r\n							</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<p>\r\n							</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-12" style="text-align:center">\r\n								<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/w6RsY5xWWsg" width="560"></iframe>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n					<!--containerfluid-->\r\n				</div>\r\n				<!--light div-->\r\n			</div>\r\n			<!--scroller-->\r\n		</div>\r\n		<!--content -->\r\n	</div>\r\n	<!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(53, 'The Team', 'TeamThreads', 4, 14, '\r\n    <div class="bb-item" id="item13">\r\n        <div class="pagenum">\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n        <div class="content">\r\n            <div class="scroller">\r\n                <div class="light">\r\n                    <h2>The Team</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <div class="container-fluid">\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4 col-md-offset-3">\r\n                                <h4 class="team">Editors</h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ul class="special">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/aparna-jairaj-884751b1">Aparna Jairaj</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/aashishsatya">Aashish Satyajith</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/pbhopalka">Piyush Bhopalka</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/kumar-tej-41297699">Kumar Tej</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/navaneeth-kishore-4b8832b5">Navaneeth Kishore</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/rachna-sasheendran-82122b110">Rachna Sasheendran</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/pavithra-a-varier-b58142110">Pavithra A Varier</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/anjanasoman">Madhumita Mohan</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                    \r\n                                     <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://www.facebook.com/abhiram.haridas.9">Abhiram Haridas</a>\r\n                                     </li>\r\n                                    \r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="http://people.cse.nitc.ac.in/pathari/">Vinod Pathari</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4">\r\n                                <h4 class="team">Designers</h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <ul class="special">\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://github.com/anasanzari">Anas Ansari</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <li>\r\n                                        <a href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/nithin-jose-tom-72b025b3">Nithin Jose Tom</a>\r\n                                    </li>\r\n                                </ul>\r\n                            </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                            <div class="col-md-4">\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                        <div class="row">\r\n                            <div class="col-md-12">\r\n                                <div class="socialbuttons">\r\n                                    <a class="social" href="https://www.facebook.com/CSEA.NITC"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/5.jpg"></a> <a class="social" href="http://assoc.cse.nitc.ac.in"><img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/6.jpg"></a>\r\n                                </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="center">Suggestions for improvement are welcome.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n                                <p class="center">As always, we are accepting articles for our next issues. Please drop us a mail at <a href="mailto:csed.newsletter@gmail.com" target="_top">csed.newsletter@gmail.com</a></p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n'),
(54, 'The Video', 'Anas ', 4, 8, '<!DOCTYPE html>\r\n\r\n<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title>\r\n	</title>\r\n</head>\r\n\r\n<body>\r\n	<div class="bb-item" id="item8">\r\n		<div class="pagenum">\r\n			9/13\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<div class="content">\r\n			<div class="scroller">\r\n				<div class="light">\r\n					<h2>Loopback''17</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n					<div class="container-fluid">\r\n						<div class="row">\r\n							A few glimpses from the CSED Alumni Meet Loopback that was conducted on Jan 14-15 here at NIT.\r\n\r\n							<p>\r\n							</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<p>\r\n							</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n							<div class="col-md-12" style="text-align:center">\r\n								<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/HkrPMOD41RY" width="560"></iframe>\r\n							</div>\r\n						</div>\r\n					</div>\r\n					<!--containerfluid-->\r\n				</div>\r\n				<!--light div-->\r\n			</div>\r\n			<!--scroller-->\r\n		</div>\r\n		<!--content -->\r\n	</div>\r\n	<!--bb-item-->\r\n</body>\r\n</html>'),
(55, 'Simulators and Emulators', 'Abhiram & Madhumita', 4, 5, '\r\n  <div class="bb-item" id="item4">\r\n    <div class="pagenum">\r\n     6/13 \r\n    </div>\r\n    <div class="content">\r\n      <div class="scroller">\r\n        <div class="light">\r\n\r\n          <h2>Simulators and Emulators</h2>\r\n           <p class="author">- <em>Abhiram & Madhumita, B. Tech CSE Batch of 2019</em></p>\r\n<style scoped="" type="text/css">\r\n                .newul li{\r\n                list-style: disc outside none;\r\n                }\r\n\r\n                </style>\r\n          <div class="container-fluid">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <p>   It’s said that “if you can’t build something, you haven’t understood it well enough”. But not everything is worth ‘building’ for the sake of ‘understanding’. As far as I am concerned, if you can tell things apart in situations where others fail, you’re good to go. We’ve all come across terms which appear to be no different from each other. Well, appearances can be deceiving. It’s intriguing and often very interesting to find the subtle differences which accurately define things that ‘appear’ to be same. In this article let’s take on one such pair - Simulators and Emulators.</p>\r\n\r\n              <p> Both the words, simulate and emulate roughly translates to mimicking of some sort. It is the purpose of this mimicking that really separates the two. For those of you who are too excited to find out the differences, fast forward to the end of the article. You will find a list of differences there. For the rest of you, let’s get started! </p>\r\n\r\n              <p>  Simulations are models that can be manipulated logically to represent how a particular system works. It is NOT a substitute for the actual target which is being simulated.  It has some characteristics that match reality and some that don’t. The purpose of simulation is to study the system internally and make useful optimizations before building a full scale project. Consider the example of a flight simulator.  A flight simulator is a device that artificially re-creates aircraft flight experience and the environment in which it flies, for pilot training, design, or other purposes.  Although the look and feel of the system closely resembles an actual flight, it cannot be used as a substitute, well because, it cannot fly! Also, while simulating, the mimicking happens at a ‘conscious’ level, meaning the user is well aware that he/she is working with a model.</p>\r\n\r\n              <p> Emulation is the process of mimicking the outwardly observable behaviour or interface to match an existing target. Emulators provide a black box implementation of the target. Emulators CAN be different from the target internally, but it ‘acts’ like the target to anything that communicates to it.  Emulators can (and most probably will be) used as a substitute for the target to be emulated. The purpose of emulation is not to study the system; it is to study the interactions of other entities with the system. Also here the mimicking happens at an ‘unconscious’ level. This does not mean that the designer is unaware of the mimicking, but the external component that interacts with the system is.</p>\r\n              </div>\r\n              <div class="col-md-6">\r\n                <p> Enough with literature, now let’s talk about software. In software terms simulators are used to study or design other systems or environments. SPICE (Simulation Program with Integrated Program Emphasis) is an example of simulator software. It is used in integrated circuits and board-level design to check the integrity of circuits before implementing them using hardware. Obviously the simulation we used to analyse the system cannot be used as a substitute to the actual circuitry. A wide variety of simulation software exists to handle anything from chemical kinetics to fluid dynamics. In fact simulation software plays a key role in applying modern computing technologies to various engineering disciplines.</p>\r\n\r\n                <p> Emulators on the other hand, are software designed to run programs which were designed for another platform (or hardware specifications) without changes to the actual program. As mentioned, the emulated platform may not be internally the same as the target. It may use other suitable implementations. What matters is the interface. Note that here the emulation is not used to study the platform but its interaction with the program. Emulators are handy tools for developers building cross platform software to test their software without the hassle of using different hardware for each platform. Also note that here the emulation is actually used as a substitute for the target. VirtualBox is a popular example of emulator software. It enables a Windows or Mac user to run any other OS from inside their own OS. With VirtualBox running a specific OS any programs written for that OS can run inside it. Bluestacks is another popular example. It is an Android emulator that enables Android apps to be run on Windows or Mac.</p>\r\n              <p>To wrap it up let’s summarize the key differences between them.</p>       \r\n              <div class = "img"> <img src="http://newsletter-cseanitc.rhcloud.com/uploads/photos/57.jpg">\r\n              </div>  \r\n\r\n              <p>There you have it, simulation and emulation – two separate modelling techniques. </p>\r\n              </div>\r\n            </div>\r\n          </div><!--containerfluid-->\r\n\r\n        </div><!--light div-->\r\n      </div><!--scroller-->\r\n    </div><!--content -->\r\n  </div><!--bb-item-->\r\n');

